00:03:44.650 --> 00:03:47.420
The question is, did
the financial crisis

00:03:47.420 --> 00:03:48.980
matter to Bitcoin?

00:03:48.980 --> 00:03:52.910
Did 2008 matter to what
happened to Bitcoin?

00:03:52.910 --> 00:03:57.050
And there are really
different opinions about this.

00:03:57.050 --> 00:04:00.460
On the one hand, you look at
it, and Bitcoin sort of exploded

00:04:00.460 --> 00:04:03.540
right when the financial
crisis happened.

00:04:03.540 --> 00:04:06.530
And on the other hand, there
are people that say no.

00:04:06.530 --> 00:04:07.630
It didn't matter.

00:04:07.630 --> 00:04:09.000
Bitcoin is a product.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:10.030
It's an innovation.

00:04:10.030 --> 00:04:12.750
It would have gone
out in the world

00:04:12.750 --> 00:04:15.050
and done what it has
done regardless of that.

00:04:15.050 --> 00:04:17.740
And some of the people
who hold that latter view

00:04:17.740 --> 00:04:21.209
are extremely intelligent
people, some of the people

00:04:21.209 --> 00:04:22.780
who are really involved in this.

00:04:22.780 --> 00:04:24.905
And they have a very
strong opinion about it,

00:04:24.905 --> 00:04:27.590
that Bitcoin is a
product, it is software.

00:04:27.590 --> 00:04:30.970
It is something that is valuable
in and of its own right.

00:04:30.970 --> 00:04:33.560
And it would have gone
out into the world

00:04:33.560 --> 00:04:37.790
and made its way regardless
of when it was released.

00:04:37.790 --> 00:04:42.910
But I can't help but
think that 2008 did matter

00:04:42.910 --> 00:04:44.750
to what happened
to Bitcoin-- that

00:04:44.750 --> 00:04:49.960
a decentralized, peer to peer
encrypted, anonymous currency

00:04:49.960 --> 00:04:53.490
system that came out at the
depths of the financial crisis

00:04:53.490 --> 00:04:57.430
struck a very strong chord
with a lot of people.

00:04:57.430 --> 00:05:00.260
And that's the "Wall
Street Journal."

00:05:00.260 --> 00:05:02.900
Mike and I write for them.

00:05:02.900 --> 00:05:06.360
And you talk about
the period of 2008.

00:05:06.360 --> 00:05:09.160
And you talk about really
the entire period of 2008,

00:05:09.160 --> 00:05:11.500
when the crisis
started, through 2012,

00:05:11.500 --> 00:05:15.520
through 2013, where you just
had the entire global financial

00:05:15.520 --> 00:05:17.930
system lurching from
crisis to crisis,

00:05:17.930 --> 00:05:21.200
just a cataclysm that threw
millions of people out

00:05:21.200 --> 00:05:25.390
of work, that just waylaid
entire economies, from here

00:05:25.390 --> 00:05:26.710
to Europe and Asia.

00:05:26.710 --> 00:05:30.880
I mean, it really was a
massive just disaster.

00:05:30.880 --> 00:05:31.380
Right?

00:05:31.380 --> 00:05:34.150
I don't need to tell you guys
what kind of disaster it was.

00:05:34.150 --> 00:05:35.660
We all lived through it.

00:05:35.660 --> 00:05:42.970
And what I think that helped
do is, you have this crisis.

00:05:42.970 --> 00:05:45.100
You have this--
not just a crisis

00:05:45.100 --> 00:05:49.700
of economies, a crisis of
daily-- stock markets-- it's

00:05:49.700 --> 00:05:50.780
a crisis of confidence.

00:05:50.780 --> 00:05:53.289
You have this system
that we're all born into,

00:05:53.289 --> 00:05:54.330
that we all grew up with.

00:05:54.330 --> 00:05:56.880
The financial edifice that
we never had to question.

00:05:56.880 --> 00:05:58.750
You never really
worried about it.

00:05:58.750 --> 00:06:02.480
Suddenly, the thing seems
unbelievably fragile

00:06:02.480 --> 00:06:04.690
and unbelievably shaky.

00:06:04.690 --> 00:06:07.900
And let's not kid
ourselves, too.

00:06:07.900 --> 00:06:08.760
It did crash.

00:06:08.760 --> 00:06:09.896
It did collapse.

00:06:09.896 --> 00:06:11.520
Governments had to
come in and bail out

00:06:11.520 --> 00:06:12.747
the companies, the banks.

00:06:12.747 --> 00:06:14.830
Governments had to come
in and prop up the system.

00:06:14.830 --> 00:06:16.790
I mean, this was an
absolute collapse.

00:06:16.790 --> 00:06:18.110
This was a problem.

00:06:18.110 --> 00:06:22.070
And into that comes Bitcoin.

00:06:22.070 --> 00:06:23.960
Nobody knows exactly
where it came from.

00:06:23.960 --> 00:06:26.970
Nobody knows who
Satoshi Nakamodo is.

00:06:26.970 --> 00:06:34.110
He releases it to this group of
cypherpunks on a mailing list.

00:06:34.110 --> 00:06:36.850
It gets very little
attention at first.

00:06:36.850 --> 00:06:39.150
And what I think is
interesting-- I'm

00:06:39.150 --> 00:06:41.030
jumping around a
little bit there--

00:06:41.030 --> 00:06:43.874
is that the cypher-- I
don't know how many of you

00:06:43.874 --> 00:06:45.290
are familiar with
the cypherpunks.

00:06:45.290 --> 00:06:48.260
But they were this group
of cryptography experts,

00:06:48.260 --> 00:06:51.110
very concerned about
issues of privacy,

00:06:51.110 --> 00:06:54.180
about issues-- all the
issues that revolve

00:06:54.180 --> 00:06:55.610
around privacy and technology.

00:06:55.610 --> 00:06:59.140
And they've been dealing with
this for decades, and decades

00:06:59.140 --> 00:07:02.560
ago, had been thinking about
a digital currency, a coin.

00:07:02.560 --> 00:07:04.450
This is one of
their prime ideas,

00:07:04.450 --> 00:07:06.540
had worked on it
for a long time.

00:07:06.540 --> 00:07:08.810
All of these
different precursors,

00:07:08.810 --> 00:07:10.780
protocoins if you
want to, they'd

00:07:10.780 --> 00:07:12.750
all failed for one
reason or another.

00:07:12.750 --> 00:07:15.880
So that by the time Nakomodo
comes around in 2008

00:07:15.880 --> 00:07:18.820
and releases Bitcoin,
they've kind of given up.

00:07:18.820 --> 00:07:19.740
They've moved on.

00:07:19.740 --> 00:07:24.700
They really did not give it
a lot of attention at first.

00:07:24.700 --> 00:07:28.530
But through this
period that we're in,

00:07:28.530 --> 00:07:33.380
2008, 2009, and the crisis, it
starts to gain some adherence.

00:07:33.380 --> 00:07:34.770
It's very small.

00:07:34.770 --> 00:07:36.780
But it starts to
gain some very, very

00:07:36.780 --> 00:07:40.400
passionate, passionate
people around this idea.

00:07:40.400 --> 00:07:43.240
And they are attached to it.

00:07:43.240 --> 00:07:45.240
And you can see this.

00:07:45.240 --> 00:07:47.070
What's really
interesting too is if you

00:07:47.070 --> 00:07:49.470
go on the old-- not
the old, the current.

00:07:49.470 --> 00:07:51.380
But if you go on the
Bitcoin message boards,

00:07:51.380 --> 00:07:53.671
you can go back and look at
the entire history of them.

00:07:53.671 --> 00:07:54.620
They're all there.

00:07:54.620 --> 00:07:55.800
It's all online.

00:07:55.800 --> 00:07:58.470
And in researching the
book, I had done this.

00:07:58.470 --> 00:07:59.880
I had gone back
and looked at it.

00:07:59.880 --> 00:08:01.696
And it's fascinating.

00:08:01.696 --> 00:08:02.320
You can see it.

00:08:02.320 --> 00:08:05.840
It goes from a couple of people,
to a couple dozen of people,

00:08:05.840 --> 00:08:08.660
to a couple of hundred people,
to thousands of people.

00:08:08.660 --> 00:08:15.709
And they are fueled by this idea
of a solution to this problem

00:08:15.709 --> 00:08:17.250
that the real world
is going through.

00:08:17.250 --> 00:08:21.050
All the time that we're seeing
these headlines, this solution

00:08:21.050 --> 00:08:25.420
of an alternative currency that
completely sidesteps everything

00:08:25.420 --> 00:08:27.530
that is giving us
all these problems.

00:08:27.530 --> 00:08:32.460
And you start to see a community
grow up around Bitcoin.

00:08:32.460 --> 00:08:35.007
And this photo, I'm very
proud of this photo.

00:08:35.007 --> 00:08:36.590
Because if you look
in the reflection,

00:08:36.590 --> 00:08:38.010
