00:11:59.030 --> 00:12:01.290
And this is what
I think is really

00:12:01.290 --> 00:12:05.790
critical, is the idea of a
culture, a idea of a community

00:12:05.790 --> 00:12:07.800
coming around this thing.

00:12:07.800 --> 00:12:10.780
Because when you think of
what a currency really is,

00:12:10.780 --> 00:12:13.220
we imbue currencies
with a lot of power.

00:12:13.220 --> 00:12:16.370
We put a lot of mythology
into what the dollar is.

00:12:16.370 --> 00:12:19.730
And who controls it actually
has a very powerful tool

00:12:19.730 --> 00:12:21.150
in that mythology.

00:12:21.150 --> 00:12:25.150
But ultimately, a currency
is really just an accounting

00:12:25.150 --> 00:12:25.660
system.

00:12:25.660 --> 00:12:28.260
It's a way for a group of people
to keep track of what they

00:12:28.260 --> 00:12:31.640
have, who owes who to what,
and to make that a very

00:12:31.640 --> 00:12:34.800
streamlined, simple process.

00:12:34.800 --> 00:12:37.770
What you have now, I think, with
Bitcoin, for the first time,

00:12:37.770 --> 00:12:40.250
is you have a way to
do that digitally.

00:12:40.250 --> 00:12:41.990
You a way to do that online.

00:12:41.990 --> 00:12:45.060
You a way to connect
people who are now

00:12:45.060 --> 00:12:47.180
being connected
through social media,

00:12:47.180 --> 00:12:49.935
but who previously
could not be connected.

00:12:49.935 --> 00:12:51.660
Who couldn't interact
with each other.

00:12:51.660 --> 00:12:54.243
Could interact with each other
on a very limited basis, right?

00:12:54.243 --> 00:12:57.690
You could talk to each other on
email, or Twitter, or whatever.

00:12:57.690 --> 00:12:59.410
Now they can do commerce
with each other.

00:12:59.410 --> 00:13:02.070
They can send each other
things, and they can pay for it.

00:13:02.070 --> 00:13:03.780
It becomes part of a whole.

00:13:03.780 --> 00:13:06.440
It becomes part
of this evolution

00:13:06.440 --> 00:13:09.240
of this online
digital community.

00:13:09.240 --> 00:13:12.940
And I think that, if you
didn't have the crisis,

00:13:12.940 --> 00:13:17.010
I don't know that that would
have really-- the crisis was

00:13:17.010 --> 00:13:18.830
really like fuel for Bitcoin.

00:13:18.830 --> 00:13:21.940
And it really kind of put a
groundswell underneath it.

00:13:21.940 --> 00:13:24.130
And the whole thing grew
in a very organic way,

00:13:24.130 --> 00:13:25.340
very viral way.

00:13:25.340 --> 00:13:27.780
There's no marketing team
that's pushing Bitcoin.

00:13:27.780 --> 00:13:30.110
There's no advertising
campaign for Bitcoin.

00:13:30.110 --> 00:13:31.840
The whole thing was
extremely organic,

00:13:31.840 --> 00:13:34.440
and it was all formed
around the community.

00:13:34.440 --> 00:13:39.510
And in a very real, real sense,
the community became Bitcoin.

00:13:39.510 --> 00:13:41.685
It wasn't just a
piece of software.

00:13:41.685 --> 00:13:43.260
It wasn't just a protocol.

00:13:43.260 --> 00:13:47.260
It is literally the community
that decides this thing

00:13:47.260 --> 00:13:50.970
matters to us, and we are going
to use it among ourselves.

00:13:50.970 --> 00:13:52.670
And that's what you end up with.

00:13:52.670 --> 00:13:55.980
And I think that's a
very powerful thing.

00:13:55.980 --> 00:14:00.290
Now, what the media still
sees is something like this.

00:14:00.290 --> 00:14:04.086
Here is Ben Lawsky's
hearing in January of 2013.

00:14:04.086 --> 00:14:06.680
Or 2014?

00:14:06.680 --> 00:14:07.540
2014.

00:14:07.540 --> 00:14:09.190
It's a random--
actually, I should

00:14:09.190 --> 00:14:10.510
have taken this slide out, too.

00:14:10.510 --> 00:14:12.422
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:14:12.422 --> 00:14:13.130
PAUL VIGNA: What?

00:14:13.130 --> 00:14:14.046
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:14:14.046 --> 00:14:16.400
PAUL VIGNA: Anyway,
you still have

00:14:16.400 --> 00:14:18.730
this sort of public
face of Bitcoin, which

00:14:18.730 --> 00:14:21.530
is Mount Gox, which
is Silk Road, which

00:14:21.530 --> 00:14:23.575
is regulators trying to
get their hands around it

00:14:23.575 --> 00:14:24.780
and hold hearings.

00:14:24.780 --> 00:14:29.160
And that becomes what
most people think

00:14:29.160 --> 00:14:30.520
of when they think of Bitcoin.

00:14:30.520 --> 00:14:32.580
But it isn't that.

00:14:32.580 --> 00:14:34.180
It really is the community.

00:14:34.180 --> 00:14:36.914
And these slides I
wanted to bring in,

00:14:36.914 --> 00:14:38.080
because they're very visual.

00:14:38.080 --> 00:14:39.410
But it's really interesting.

00:14:39.410 --> 00:14:42.380
The guy, the large gentleman
with the frizzy hair

00:14:42.380 --> 00:14:45.530
and the beard, his
name is Hooroo Jackson.

00:14:45.530 --> 00:14:50.800
And he had invested in Bitcoin
early, and got rich on Bitcoin,

00:14:50.800 --> 00:14:52.419
and used it to make a movie.

00:14:52.419 --> 00:14:53.960
The movie is called
"Aimy in a Cage."

00:14:53.960 --> 00:14:58.500
He was an aspiring director, and
he was able to fund it himself

00:14:58.500 --> 00:14:59.400
through Bitcoin.

00:14:59.400 --> 00:15:00.720
He hasn't released it yet.

00:15:00.720 --> 00:15:01.912
He completed it.

00:15:01.912 --> 00:15:03.620
And I just wanted to
pull up some slides.

00:15:03.620 --> 00:15:05.240
Because again, it's
just an example

00:15:05.240 --> 00:15:10.880
of how people were using this
for more than just a currency,

00:15:10.880 --> 00:15:11.510
a token.

00:15:11.510 --> 00:15:13.551
This became something that
became a cultural art,

00:15:13.551 --> 00:15:14.880
being part of their lives.

00:15:14.880 --> 00:15:17.632
And hopefully, Hooroo's
movie gets out there.

00:15:17.632 --> 00:15:19.590
I don't know what he's
going to do with it yet,

00:15:19.590 --> 00:15:22.060
but I just think it's
very-- it's not actually

00:15:22.060 --> 00:15:24.260
about Bitcoin.

00:15:24.260 --> 00:15:26.470
This is Austin and
Becky Craig, who

00:15:26.470 --> 00:15:32.110
in 2013 wanted to travel around
the world using only Bitcoin

00:15:32.110 --> 00:15:33.950
to prove that it could be done.

00:15:33.950 --> 00:15:35.290
And they did it.

00:15:35.290 --> 00:15:38.140
They drove across
country from Utah,

00:15:38.140 --> 00:15:39.534
their home in Provo, Utah.

00:15:39.534 --> 00:15:40.450
They came to New York.

00:15:40.450 --> 00:15:42.710
I met them at a
Brooklyn pizza place.

00:15:42.710 --> 00:15:43.770
That's where they are.

00:15:43.770 --> 00:15:45.774
That was supposed
to take Bitcoin.

00:15:45.774 --> 00:15:47.940
It was the only place in
the city that took Bitcoin.

00:15:47.940 --> 00:15:49.907
So because they were
only spending Bitcoin,

00:15:49.907 --> 00:15:51.490
they went to this
Brooklyn pizza place

00:15:51.490 --> 00:15:53.282
to buy their pizza with Bitcoin.

00:15:53.282 --> 00:15:54.490
And then they got on a plane.

00:15:54.490 --> 00:15:55.323
They flew to Europe.

00:15:55.323 --> 00:15:56.460
They flew to Asia.

00:15:56.460 --> 00:15:58.380
And they managed to do it.

00:15:58.380 --> 00:16:02.310
They managed to go around the
world spending only Bitcoin.

00:16:02.310 --> 00:16:06.830
Did involve some homeless
nights, some foodless nights.

00:16:06.830 --> 00:16:08.130
It was not easy.

00:16:08.130 --> 00:16:09.740
But they did it.

00:16:09.740 --> 00:16:13.240
And they showed in doing
it that, again, this

00:16:13.240 --> 00:16:16.100
was a community that was
growing up around this thing.

00:16:16.100 --> 00:16:18.680
And it was really taking flight.

00:16:18.680 --> 00:16:21.350
No pun intended, actually.

00:16:21.350 --> 00:16:23.620
It really was growing.

00:16:23.620 --> 00:16:25.556
So this is what happened
all through 2008,

00:16:25.556 --> 00:16:30.160
2009, '10, '11, '12, '13,
this community kind of grows.

00:16:30.160 --> 00:16:36.320
And in 2013, it really kind of
explodes into the mainstream.

00:16:36.320 --> 00:16:39.980
And now journalists are
getting interested in it.

00:16:39.980 --> 00:16:41.625
The media's taking notice of it.

00:16:41.625 --> 00:16:43.250
You still have all
the salacious stuff.

00:16:43.250 --> 00:16:45.110
You still have all
the salacious stories.

00:16:45.110 --> 00:16:47.482
But suddenly, this thing
seems to come out of nowhere.

00:16:47.482 --> 00:16:49.190
And people are saying,
oh my god, Bitcoin

00:16:49.190 --> 00:16:51.160
is going to take over the world.

00:16:51.160 --> 00:16:53.180
It didn't really
come out of nowhere.

00:16:53.180 --> 00:16:55.560
And it really wasn't going
to take over the world.

00:16:55.560 --> 00:16:57.920
And I think that was
a problem for it.

00:16:57.920 --> 00:17:01.410
Because it appeared
that, overnight, this

00:17:01.410 --> 00:17:03.720
was going to be a new
way of doing things.

00:17:03.720 --> 00:17:07.319
And that was part of
what fueled the rise up

00:17:07.319 --> 00:17:09.660
to $1,000, the speculation.

00:17:09.660 --> 00:17:12.569
Everyone goes crazy over it.

00:17:12.569 --> 00:17:16.490
And it put far, far too
much on what is still

00:17:16.490 --> 00:17:17.849
something that is being built.

00:17:17.849 --> 00:17:19.723
I mean, it's really
important to keep in mind

00:17:19.723 --> 00:17:21.790
that Bitcoin is still
in a beta phase.

00:17:21.790 --> 00:17:23.569
They are still
building the protocol.

00:17:23.569 --> 00:17:25.339
They're still
building the system.

00:17:25.339 --> 00:17:27.980
And I think that that
actually kind of came

00:17:27.980 --> 00:17:30.850
to be a problem for
Bitcoin, because it

00:17:30.850 --> 00:17:32.110
couldn't fulfil those dreams.

00:17:32.110 --> 00:17:35.880
It couldn't fulfill everything
that people were putting on it,

00:17:35.880 --> 00:17:38.100
and it starts to
have some problems.

00:17:38.100 --> 00:17:41.694
And you can see there, that's
just in the first quarter.

00:17:41.694 --> 00:17:43.110
And then the rest
of these slides,

00:17:43.110 --> 00:17:45.234
actually, I should give
credit where credit is due.

00:17:45.234 --> 00:17:47.050
I cribbed these off
of CoinDesk which

00:17:47.050 --> 00:17:48.770
is a Bitcoin news service.

00:17:48.770 --> 00:17:51.730
They do a quarterly
"State of Bitcoin" report.

00:17:51.730 --> 00:17:53.910
It's actually very, very good.

00:17:53.910 --> 00:17:56.480
2013, Bitcoin hits
its all time high.

00:17:56.480 --> 00:17:58.530
Falls all through 2014.

00:17:58.530 --> 00:18:01.040
The price comes down,
because this speculation

00:18:01.040 --> 00:18:03.080
starts to seep out of it.

00:18:03.080 --> 00:18:05.580
It's not going to take
over the world overnight.

00:18:05.580 --> 00:18:09.280
It is not going to become
this thing that challenges

00:18:09.280 --> 00:18:11.170
the homogeny of the US dollar.

00:18:11.170 --> 00:18:13.367
It was not going to happen.

00:18:13.367 --> 00:18:15.700
People start to get a little
disillusioned with Bitcoin.

00:18:15.700 --> 00:18:18.140
They start to get a
little bored with Bitcoin.

00:18:18.140 --> 00:18:23.230
But what was happening
is a different group

00:18:23.230 --> 00:18:25.900
of people was starting to
come into the Bitcoin world.

00:18:25.900 --> 00:18:29.610
And to call them, use a loose
term, call them the suits.

00:18:29.610 --> 00:18:32.250
Money was starting to
get ahold of this idea

00:18:32.250 --> 00:18:34.260
that there was
something valuable here.

00:18:34.260 --> 00:18:37.490
The techies, the libertarians,
had built something.

00:18:37.490 --> 00:18:39.260
They had put their
passion into it.

00:18:39.260 --> 00:18:41.020
They had given a lot to it.

00:18:41.020 --> 00:18:44.420
And they built this thing, and
they showed that it had value.

00:18:44.420 --> 00:18:47.570
Even when you have a situation
like, say, that the Silk Road,

00:18:47.570 --> 00:18:49.750
which is an online drug bazaar.

00:18:49.750 --> 00:18:51.760
It is clearly illegal.

00:18:51.760 --> 00:18:55.760
But as a use case for Bitcoin,
it showed that this coin works.

00:18:55.760 --> 00:18:58.120
People could trade online.

00:18:58.120 --> 00:19:01.430
They could buy and sell online,
and they could send the money

00:19:01.430 --> 00:19:03.880
to each other directly online.

00:19:03.880 --> 00:19:05.590
That's a powerful thing.

00:19:05.590 --> 00:19:07.680
Then you start seeing
the suits get involved.

00:19:07.680 --> 00:19:10.910
And about $380
million of VC money

00:19:10.910 --> 00:19:13.302
went into Bitcoin in 2014.

00:19:13.302 --> 00:19:14.760
These are two of
the big deals that

00:19:14.760 --> 00:19:19.330
happened this past quarter--
Coinbase and 21 is a company.

00:19:19.330 --> 00:19:24.080
They got about $200 million
between the two of them.

00:19:24.080 --> 00:19:26.045
And people start
talking about, they

00:19:26.045 --> 00:19:27.960
start comparing Bitcoin
to the internet.

00:19:27.960 --> 00:19:30.110
This is another kind
of valuable chart.

00:19:30.110 --> 00:19:32.720
It shows where
Bitcoin was in 2014,

00:19:32.720 --> 00:19:35.430
in terms of VC
investment, compared

00:19:35.430 --> 00:19:37.850
to the internet in 1995.

00:19:37.850 --> 00:19:39.940
And you can see
that there's money.

00:19:39.940 --> 00:19:42.420
There's real money
coming into Bitcoin.

00:19:42.420 --> 00:19:45.470
People who care about
making a profit,

00:19:45.470 --> 00:19:47.000
who care about
building things that

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:49.370
are going to be good for
them in the long term,

00:19:49.370 --> 00:19:51.290
are starting to get
interested in it.

00:19:51.290 --> 00:19:54.860
So that has become--
and I think, actually,

00:19:54.860 --> 00:19:58.960
in 2015 that's a huge story,
the idea that Wall Street is

00:19:58.960 --> 00:20:02.140
getting interested in Bitcoin
as a technology, as a product.

00:20:02.140 --> 00:20:07.160
As you see sort of the
cultural part of it fade away,

00:20:07.160 --> 00:20:10.850
you're starting to see this
business case be made for it.

00:20:10.850 --> 00:20:15.310
But Bitcoin is kind of
reaching a crossroads.

00:20:15.310 --> 00:20:17.270
The really passionate
people that

00:20:17.270 --> 00:20:19.970
were going to come on board
early-- the early adopters,

00:20:19.970 --> 00:20:22.620
the techies, the
libertarians, the artists

00:20:22.620 --> 00:20:25.200
that really were looking
for something new--

00:20:25.200 --> 00:20:30.500
that community has kind
of saturated itself.

00:20:30.500 --> 00:20:32.440
Bitcoin has saturated
that community.

00:20:32.440 --> 00:20:35.910
Can you find people outside of
that that are interested enough

00:20:35.910 --> 00:20:37.180
to get on board?

00:20:37.180 --> 00:20:39.860
That's another
question right now.

00:20:39.860 --> 00:20:41.050
And it's a problem.

00:20:41.050 --> 00:20:44.250
This is the number of
Bitcoin accepting businesses

00:20:44.250 --> 00:20:45.640
added in each quarter.

00:20:45.640 --> 00:20:47.400
And you can see the
number of businesses

00:20:47.400 --> 00:20:50.240
are-- the growth rate
of the businesses

00:20:50.240 --> 00:20:52.090
is starting to level off.

00:20:52.090 --> 00:20:53.470
Because businesses,
they take it.

00:20:53.470 --> 00:20:53.980
They accept it.

00:20:53.980 --> 00:20:55.938
They say, oh yeah, this
is kind of interesting.

00:20:55.938 --> 00:20:58.780
At the last, we can use
it as a marketing thing

00:20:58.780 --> 00:21:00.840
to attract this crowd.

00:21:00.840 --> 00:21:02.620
But they're not
finding that there's

00:21:02.620 --> 00:21:04.760
a lot of business
being done with it.

00:21:04.760 --> 00:21:07.439
So you're having fewer
and fewer businesses--

00:21:07.439 --> 00:21:08.730
even though you have big names.

00:21:08.730 --> 00:21:11.460
Microsoft is using it
in a limited sense.

00:21:11.460 --> 00:21:13.257
Dell is using it
in a limited sense.

00:21:13.257 --> 00:21:15.590
Big companies are understanding
there's something there.

00:21:15.590 --> 00:21:17.420
They want to experiment with it.

00:21:17.420 --> 00:21:20.580
But they're not seeing a
huge groundswell of business

00:21:20.580 --> 00:21:21.440
from it.

00:21:21.440 --> 00:21:23.720
So that's another issue.

00:21:23.720 --> 00:21:25.314
And this is another slide.

00:21:25.314 --> 00:21:26.730
Actually, these
next few slides, I

00:21:26.730 --> 00:21:28.700
think I'm going to leave
them up for Mike when

00:21:28.700 --> 00:21:29.674
he starts talking.

00:21:29.674 --> 00:21:31.340
Because this kind of
really gets to what

00:21:31.340 --> 00:21:34.080
you're interested in Mike.

00:21:34.080 --> 00:21:36.630
What is Bitcoin
going to be about?

00:21:36.630 --> 00:21:38.440
What is Bitcoin for?

00:21:38.440 --> 00:21:42.270
Is it really for
first-world US citizens

00:21:42.270 --> 00:21:44.980
who have access to all kinds
of banking services, who

00:21:44.980 --> 00:21:47.540
have access to any kind
of credit they need,

00:21:47.540 --> 00:21:49.090
using another one?

00:21:49.090 --> 00:21:52.400
Or is it really about people
who live in emerging markets.

00:21:52.400 --> 00:21:55.150
People who don't have
access to banking services.

00:21:55.150 --> 00:21:57.600
People who can't really
build up the kind of wealth

00:21:57.600 --> 00:21:59.400
that we take for granted.

00:21:59.400 --> 00:22:02.790
That, I think, is where
Bitcoin-- that is really

00:22:02.790 --> 00:22:04.730
what I find very
fascinating about Bitcoin.

00:22:04.730 --> 00:22:08.711
That's what I think is Bitcoin's
biggest, to use the phrase, use

00:22:08.711 --> 00:22:09.210
case.

00:22:09.210 --> 00:22:11.170
I think that is where
Bitcoin is going

00:22:11.170 --> 00:22:13.010
to really prove its worth.

00:22:13.010 --> 00:22:17.620
And I will say,
too, me personally,

00:22:17.620 --> 00:22:21.525
when I got involved in
journalism, I did it-- well,

00:22:21.525 --> 00:22:24.480
when I got in journalism, I
did it because I needed a job.

00:22:24.480 --> 00:22:26.607
And my only salable asset
was writing and editing.

00:22:26.607 --> 00:22:28.190
It was the only thing
I could do well,

00:22:28.190 --> 00:22:30.080
so I got a job in journalism.

00:22:30.080 --> 00:22:32.340
But the reason I
stayed with it was

00:22:32.340 --> 00:22:35.695
because I wanted to be able
to tell stories that I thought

00:22:35.695 --> 00:22:36.320
were important.

00:22:36.320 --> 00:22:38.160
I wanted to be able
to tell stories

00:22:38.160 --> 00:22:40.720
that I thought mattered
in terms of improving

00:22:40.720 --> 00:22:42.180
the human condition.

00:22:42.180 --> 00:22:45.140
And in 2013, I
realized that I think

00:22:45.140 --> 00:22:47.770
Bitcoin can help improve
the human condition,

00:22:47.770 --> 00:22:49.560
and that it is
part of that story.

00:22:49.560 --> 00:22:51.880
And I was one of
those people that

00:22:51.880 --> 00:22:55.510
became very, very-- that
groundswell came under my feet,

00:22:55.510 --> 00:22:57.320
and I became very
obsessed with Bitcoin,

00:22:57.320 --> 00:22:58.520
and I got very into it.

00:22:58.520 --> 00:23:01.103
And Michael also, and that's why
we wanted to write this book,

00:23:01.103 --> 00:23:04.300
because we think there
is a very, very big story

00:23:04.300 --> 00:23:06.940
to tell here, and we
wanted to be a part of it

00:23:06.940 --> 00:23:08.110
in any kind of way.

00:23:08.110 --> 00:23:11.680
For me, writing stories is
my way of being a part of it.

00:23:11.680 --> 00:23:12.840
I'm not a VC.

00:23:12.840 --> 00:23:13.910
I'm not an entrepreneur.

00:23:13.910 --> 00:23:15.659
I'm not going to go
into those businesses.

00:23:15.659 --> 00:23:18.430
I'm not going to start
up own Bitcoin app.

00:23:18.430 --> 00:23:19.550
I want to tell a story.

00:23:19.550 --> 00:23:21.650
I think Bitcoin's a
very-- I think it's

00:23:21.650 --> 00:23:23.740
a critically important story.

00:23:23.740 --> 00:23:25.440
But I think it is
also a story that

00:23:25.440 --> 00:23:28.770
is it at the very, very early--
I keep saying very, very.

00:23:28.770 --> 00:23:30.610
It's at very early stages.

00:23:30.610 --> 00:23:32.130
This thing is only
six years old.

00:23:32.130 --> 00:23:33.670
Like I said, it
is still in beta.

00:23:33.670 --> 00:23:35.480
It is not even in version 1.0.

00:23:35.480 --> 00:23:37.340
They are still
building this thing.

00:23:37.340 --> 00:23:40.170
Over the next 5,
10, 15, 20 years,

00:23:40.170 --> 00:23:42.600
you are going to see this go
in places that we can't even

00:23:42.600 --> 00:23:44.160
think of right now.

00:23:44.160 --> 00:23:48.450
The way I look at it is I
think it's as if this is 1896,

00:23:48.450 --> 00:23:51.300
and we're all living in
our little rural community

00:23:51.300 --> 00:23:53.520
with dirt rows that
your horses go down.

00:23:53.520 --> 00:23:56.502
And you just saw the first
horseless carriage go by.

00:23:56.502 --> 00:23:58.210
And it scared the hell
out of your horse.

00:23:58.210 --> 00:23:59.140
It might have scared your wife.

00:23:59.140 --> 00:23:59.950
It scared you.

00:23:59.950 --> 00:24:01.200
And you don't know what it is.

00:24:01.200 --> 00:24:03.460
And it's very odd,
and it's very unusual.

00:24:03.460 --> 00:24:07.950
And your initial reaction
is, that thing has to go.

00:24:07.950 --> 00:24:09.399
That thing is dangerous.

00:24:09.399 --> 00:24:10.940
That thing is going
to hurt somebody.

00:24:10.940 --> 00:24:12.570
We've got to get
rid of that thing.

00:24:12.570 --> 00:24:14.800
There's a quote by--
and I'm jumping around

00:24:14.800 --> 00:24:16.460
in my historical
references here--

00:24:16.460 --> 00:24:18.340
there's a quote by
a second century

00:24:18.340 --> 00:24:22.840
Italian writer named Tertullian,
who had said the first reaction

00:24:22.840 --> 00:24:25.220
to truth is always hatred.

00:24:25.220 --> 00:24:28.070
And I think that's a really
kind of interesting way

00:24:28.070 --> 00:24:30.000
to think about new ideas.

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:34.250
The visceral reaction to a
new idea, usually, is hatred.

00:24:36.860 --> 00:24:37.780
It's doubt.

00:24:37.780 --> 00:24:39.040
It's skepticism.

00:24:39.040 --> 00:24:40.270
It's nah, this can't work.

00:24:40.270 --> 00:24:41.570
And I'm that way, too.

00:24:41.570 --> 00:24:43.732
When I first heard of
Bitcoin, I was the same way.

00:24:43.732 --> 00:24:45.440
I said, I'm not writing
about this thing.

00:24:45.440 --> 00:24:46.270
This is a scam.

00:24:46.270 --> 00:24:47.280
This is a con.

00:24:47.280 --> 00:24:48.310
It's a Ponzi scheme.

00:24:48.310 --> 00:24:49.950
It's not going to last.

00:24:49.950 --> 00:24:52.940
I actually did, I said I
refused to write about it.

00:24:52.940 --> 00:24:54.620
But I kept thinking about it.

00:24:54.620 --> 00:24:57.767
And I kept reading about it, and
it kept popping up in places.

00:24:57.767 --> 00:24:59.350
And then I started
getting interested.

00:24:59.350 --> 00:25:02.090
And then I started reading more,
and I started writing more.

00:25:02.090 --> 00:25:04.820
And the more I read, the
more I saw there was to read.

00:25:04.820 --> 00:25:07.600
And the more I wrote, the
more I saw there was to write,

00:25:07.600 --> 00:25:10.190
until the story just got
bigger and bigger and bigger.

00:25:10.190 --> 00:25:12.230
And I think it is
going to keep getting

00:25:12.230 --> 00:25:14.210
bigger and bigger and bigger.

00:25:14.210 --> 00:25:17.787
And where it goes from
here is not exactly clear.

00:25:17.787 --> 00:25:19.370
And that's where I'm
going to hand off

00:25:19.370 --> 00:25:21.411
to Mike, because Mike is
going to talk about some

00:25:21.411 --> 00:25:22.890
of those things.

00:25:22.890 --> 00:25:24.550
And I don't think
I went over time.

00:25:24.550 --> 00:25:25.460
I hope I didn't.

00:25:25.460 --> 00:25:28.810
But I'm going to hand off
to my esteemed colleague

00:25:28.810 --> 00:25:30.498
and co-author, Mike Casey.

