00:27:34.450 --> 00:27:35.397
You know?

00:27:35.397 --> 00:27:36.480
I'm an Aussie, by the way.

00:27:36.480 --> 00:27:38.480
So I'm not going to get
that accent quite right.

00:27:38.480 --> 00:27:42.744
But anyway, this matter is, I
think-- this is a judgement.

00:27:42.744 --> 00:27:44.660
I certainly don't mean
to pick on Schwab here.

00:27:44.660 --> 00:27:48.300
Because the idea that you
have a centralized algorithm--

00:27:48.300 --> 00:27:50.150
and this is the point.

00:27:50.150 --> 00:27:51.790
The idea that this
is not actually

00:27:51.790 --> 00:27:53.790
your intelligent investors
that are [INAUDIBLE].

00:27:53.790 --> 00:27:56.750
Of course, the algorithm
is owned by Schwab.

00:27:56.750 --> 00:27:59.620
It's not your algorithm.

00:27:59.620 --> 00:28:03.310
It flies in the face of the
Bitcoin ethos, if you like.

00:28:03.310 --> 00:28:06.280
That the algorithm really
cannot belong to anybody.

00:28:06.280 --> 00:28:08.190
It needs to belong
to the community,

00:28:08.190 --> 00:28:13.510
and it needs to
be something that

00:28:13.510 --> 00:28:16.240
doesn't allow the centralization
of the information,

00:28:16.240 --> 00:28:19.710
and therefore the idea that
some powerful corporate interest

00:28:19.710 --> 00:28:22.090
could just morph into HAL.

00:28:22.090 --> 00:28:24.470
And I'm not here to pick on
Schwab about this, of course.

00:28:24.470 --> 00:28:28.087
Because algorithms are
essentially owned by companies

00:28:28.087 --> 00:28:30.170
all over the world, and
I'd be remiss to point out

00:28:30.170 --> 00:28:31.910
that I'm speaking at the
offices of the company

00:28:31.910 --> 00:28:34.034
that owns the most powerful
algorithm in the world.

00:28:34.034 --> 00:28:37.290
So there's nothing wrong
with this principle.

00:28:37.290 --> 00:28:40.530
It's just that it
speaks, I think,

00:28:40.530 --> 00:28:46.080
to what drives the dream of the
Bitcoin world, the idea that we

00:28:46.080 --> 00:28:49.100
can shift this out in
a decentralized way.

00:28:49.100 --> 00:28:53.240
And it matters right
now because, as Bitcoin

00:28:53.240 --> 00:28:56.060
goes through this
crossroads process,

00:28:56.060 --> 00:28:58.620
there's all sorts of
other interested parties

00:28:58.620 --> 00:29:03.162
who-- really noting how
important it could be.

00:29:03.162 --> 00:29:04.620
We were talking
over lunch actually

00:29:04.620 --> 00:29:08.050
about how the-- there's a
struggle that those of us who

00:29:08.050 --> 00:29:11.770
think Bitcoin's an important
issue face with the way

00:29:11.770 --> 00:29:13.130
the mainstream perceives it.

00:29:13.130 --> 00:29:15.620
As much as there is this
incredibly passionate community

00:29:15.620 --> 00:29:16.679
that grew very quickly.

00:29:16.679 --> 00:29:18.470
It seems as if they've
reached a roadblock.

00:29:18.470 --> 00:29:21.276
Because once you step outside
of the realm of the techies

00:29:21.276 --> 00:29:23.930
and the libertarians,
the utopians,

00:29:23.930 --> 00:29:26.310
the fringe dwellers if you like.

00:29:26.310 --> 00:29:28.730
Not to cast aspersions
on all of you tech types,

00:29:28.730 --> 00:29:32.659
but there is something--
you are not middle America.

00:29:32.659 --> 00:29:34.200
Middle America has
a problem with it,

00:29:34.200 --> 00:29:36.170
because they perceive and see
all sorts of other problems

00:29:36.170 --> 00:29:36.980
with it.

00:29:36.980 --> 00:29:41.290
What's happening, interestingly,
is that these guys

00:29:41.290 --> 00:29:42.390
are getting involved.

00:29:42.390 --> 00:29:45.030
They're getting involved, and
mainstream is going, what?

00:29:45.030 --> 00:29:46.196
The New York Stock Exchange?

00:29:46.196 --> 00:29:48.904
What are they dabbling
in Bitcoin for?

00:29:48.904 --> 00:29:51.070
Why would you ever want to
get involved in something

00:29:51.070 --> 00:29:54.100
that's being run by criminals?

00:29:54.100 --> 00:29:56.260
And yet, it's happening
over and over again.

00:29:56.260 --> 00:29:57.635
So you can see
the New York Stock

00:29:57.635 --> 00:29:59.040
Exchange invested in Coinbase.

00:29:59.040 --> 00:30:01.110
Duncan Niederauer who
just coincidentally

00:30:01.110 --> 00:30:05.870
was the previous CEO of NYSE,
he joined a Bitcoin swap side,

00:30:05.870 --> 00:30:08.120
TeraExchange.

00:30:08.120 --> 00:30:11.260
This one's really
interesting-- Blythe Masters.

00:30:11.260 --> 00:30:14.216
some People see her as
sort of a sinister figure,

00:30:14.216 --> 00:30:15.340
but she really is a genius.

00:30:15.340 --> 00:30:18.220
She created credit
default swaps, really.

00:30:18.220 --> 00:30:20.950
And she's now left
JPM, JP Morgan,

00:30:20.950 --> 00:30:23.390
and is the CEO of Digital
Asset Holdings, which

00:30:23.390 --> 00:30:25.750
is an interesting
new settlement--

00:30:25.750 --> 00:30:29.740
digital currency and digital
asset settlement service.

00:30:29.740 --> 00:30:31.920
NASDAQ not investing,
but they're certainly

00:30:31.920 --> 00:30:33.877
providing the tech
for [INAUDIBLE] market

00:30:33.877 --> 00:30:35.210
to build a new Bitcoin exchange.

00:30:35.210 --> 00:30:37.810
UBS just announced a
new block chain lab.

00:30:37.810 --> 00:30:41.430
And Jamie Dimon, who spoke
disparagingly about Bitcoin

00:30:41.430 --> 00:30:43.460
about a year ago,
now says there is

00:30:43.460 --> 00:30:47.110
much for us-- that is JP
Morgan-- to learn from Bitcoin.

00:30:47.110 --> 00:30:48.980
So this is a sign.

00:30:48.980 --> 00:30:53.420
These guys are now
getting interested.

00:30:53.420 --> 00:30:58.600
And it's important, in the
context of this centralization

00:30:58.600 --> 00:31:01.190
versus decentralization debate.

00:31:01.190 --> 00:31:05.340
Because they're all
profit-seeking companies,

00:31:05.340 --> 00:31:06.530
quite rightfully so.

00:31:06.530 --> 00:31:10.240
I mean, as Peter Thiel
reminded us recently,

00:31:10.240 --> 00:31:12.460
you need the search
for monopoly.

00:31:12.460 --> 00:31:15.667
You need the search for
profit to drive innovation.

00:31:15.667 --> 00:31:17.500
The challenge-- and
I'll get to this later--

00:31:17.500 --> 00:31:20.680
is how do you prevent
that monopolizing process

00:31:20.680 --> 00:31:23.770
from becoming something that
kills innovation, that stifles

00:31:23.770 --> 00:31:26.850
growth, and that ultimately
turns the rent seeking

00:31:26.850 --> 00:31:30.380
activities that are inherent
to monopolies into something

00:31:30.380 --> 00:31:31.672
really quite destructive.

00:31:31.672 --> 00:31:34.130
And this is the thing I want
to come to in a little moment.

00:31:34.130 --> 00:31:40.720
But what's happening as
this corporate mainstream

00:31:40.720 --> 00:31:41.870
interest is growing?

00:31:41.870 --> 00:31:44.480
We saw Paul lined out
all the VC money that's

00:31:44.480 --> 00:31:46.730
coming into Bitcoin.

00:31:46.730 --> 00:31:48.130
This is another part of it.

00:31:48.130 --> 00:31:48.629
You know?

00:31:48.629 --> 00:31:51.320
The Wall Street and other
interests, what all of them

00:31:51.320 --> 00:31:52.540
are saying is this.

00:31:52.540 --> 00:31:56.830
I like the blockchain,
but I don't like Bitcoin.

00:31:56.830 --> 00:32:01.950
And this is something that gets
people in the Bitcoin community

00:32:01.950 --> 00:32:02.680
kind of upset.

00:32:05.200 --> 00:32:07.420
It need not, I think.

00:32:07.420 --> 00:32:10.760
But there's an enormous
amount of passion caught up

00:32:10.760 --> 00:32:13.935
in what that represents to
people in this community.

00:32:17.210 --> 00:32:23.220
What they're talking about, and
why people get upset about it,

00:32:23.220 --> 00:32:26.760
is that they say, look,
it's impossible to have

00:32:26.760 --> 00:32:29.120
a blockchain without a coin.

00:32:29.120 --> 00:32:31.630
This idea that you
had no digital value,

00:32:31.630 --> 00:32:37.080
because you need this coin
to secure the blockchain.

00:32:37.080 --> 00:32:39.880
If you have all these miners,
all these participants

00:32:39.880 --> 00:32:43.270
confirming transactions,
why on earth

00:32:43.270 --> 00:32:45.540
are they going to
participate in this network

00:32:45.540 --> 00:32:47.480
if you can't reward
them in some way?

00:32:47.480 --> 00:32:50.790
So the idea is that the
coin, that token of value,

00:32:50.790 --> 00:32:53.960
is critical for the building
of value, the incentive

00:32:53.960 --> 00:32:55.760
system that builds
the consensus model,

00:32:55.760 --> 00:33:01.050
and ultimately, therefore, the
security of the ledger itself.

00:33:01.050 --> 00:33:03.750
It's not clear that
they're necessarily right.

00:33:03.750 --> 00:33:06.730
Now, they are right on
the fundamental question

00:33:06.730 --> 00:33:08.530
of decentralization.

00:33:08.530 --> 00:33:12.254
But if you just switch
this around a little bit,

00:33:12.254 --> 00:33:13.920
and we just think
that, well, what about

00:33:13.920 --> 00:33:16.860
if we had a centralized
Block chain?

00:33:16.860 --> 00:33:20.230
Or better put, what if we had
a permissioned blockchain,

00:33:20.230 --> 00:33:25.830
whereby the nodes, the
computing-- those that

00:33:25.830 --> 00:33:28.580
are providing compute resources
to the process of processing

00:33:28.580 --> 00:33:33.960
transactions were actually
given some sort of authority

00:33:33.960 --> 00:33:34.970
to do so?

00:33:34.970 --> 00:33:39.310
That there was some entity
that said, you know what?

00:33:39.310 --> 00:33:41.792
You guys are going to
participate in this,

00:33:41.792 --> 00:33:43.000
and here are the reasons why.

00:33:43.000 --> 00:33:44.958
And there's a vested
interest in participating.

00:33:44.958 --> 00:33:49.440
And for that reason,
we don't need the coin.

00:33:49.440 --> 00:33:52.310
Because we've got an
authority to do so,

00:33:52.310 --> 00:33:53.810
and we have a reason
to do so, which

00:33:53.810 --> 00:33:57.160
is kind of the legal imperative,
the mandate, the charter,

00:33:57.160 --> 00:33:59.170
whatever you want to
call it, to do so.

00:33:59.170 --> 00:34:03.090
So we're already actually, to
some extent, in this world.

00:34:03.090 --> 00:34:06.680
Where we have
permissionless blockchains,

00:34:06.680 --> 00:34:09.215
Bitcoin being the best
known-- some of the alt coins

00:34:09.215 --> 00:34:10.420
like Litecoin.

00:34:10.420 --> 00:34:15.570
And Ethereum, the
remarkably expansive idea

00:34:15.570 --> 00:34:19.115
of a new versatile blockchain
that Vitalik Buterin,

00:34:19.115 --> 00:34:23.909
the wunderkind developer
came up with, all of which

00:34:23.909 --> 00:34:27.489
depend on the idea that anybody
can come in and participate

00:34:27.489 --> 00:34:28.810
as a miner.

00:34:28.810 --> 00:34:31.029
And then you get
permissioned Blockchains.

00:34:31.029 --> 00:34:32.820
Ripple is probably the
best known of these.

00:34:32.820 --> 00:34:35.090
I'm sure you've probably
heard of Ripple.

00:34:35.090 --> 00:34:37.600
Where there are gateways
that participate.

00:34:37.600 --> 00:34:40.710
And they're ultimately
given this role.

00:34:40.710 --> 00:34:43.050
And then there's this
newcomers on the block,

00:34:43.050 --> 00:34:48.300
Aris Industries out of
London, and Hyperledger.

00:34:48.300 --> 00:34:51.000
And they're building
blockchains that

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:54.750
could be used in corporate
settings, where the focus is

00:34:54.750 --> 00:34:59.040
on the power of the ledger
and the smart contracts that

00:34:59.040 --> 00:35:03.910
work within them, rather than
necessarily on coins and value.

00:35:03.910 --> 00:35:08.610
But when the
bitcoiners come back

00:35:08.610 --> 00:35:14.460
and say, look, this isn't going
to work, you just can't do it,

00:35:14.460 --> 00:35:18.350
it still evolves into
this question about why

00:35:18.350 --> 00:35:20.880
these companies care about it.

00:35:20.880 --> 00:35:22.600
And at the end of
the day, there needs

00:35:22.600 --> 00:35:25.510
to be a kind of commercial
use for blockchains.

00:35:25.510 --> 00:35:28.670
So companies are
worried about Bitcoin,

00:35:28.670 --> 00:35:32.330
because it has these
sort of broader concerns

00:35:32.330 --> 00:35:34.950
that the general public
is worried about.

00:35:34.950 --> 00:35:39.280
It is, at the moment, too
volatile as a functioning

00:35:39.280 --> 00:35:39.780
currency.

00:35:39.780 --> 00:35:41.321
There is this problem
of criminality.

00:35:41.321 --> 00:35:45.490
And there is the insecurity
that digital wallets have.

00:35:45.490 --> 00:35:48.440
And some of these
really are, in my mind,

00:35:48.440 --> 00:35:49.990
not particularly big issues.

00:35:49.990 --> 00:35:54.350
Because I do feel as if
innovation, even regulation,

00:35:54.350 --> 00:35:56.340
and just general
network effects,

00:35:56.340 --> 00:35:58.520
will eventually
resolve some of these.

00:35:58.520 --> 00:36:02.150
Probably of greater
concern-- these

00:36:02.150 --> 00:36:06.160
concerns that I think more
sophisticated analysis bring

00:36:06.160 --> 00:36:10.790
forth and that are focused
on the protocol itself.

00:36:10.790 --> 00:36:14.280
It has scalability limits,
particularly in terms of data.

00:36:14.280 --> 00:36:16.680
The fact that it takes
10 minutes to finish

00:36:16.680 --> 00:36:18.390
a block-- this is a Bitcoin.

00:36:18.390 --> 00:36:20.300
Other alt coins are
much faster than this.

00:36:20.300 --> 00:36:22.237
It takes an hour to have
a final confirmation.

00:36:22.237 --> 00:36:24.820
And then of course, you've got
this problem of the mining arms

00:36:24.820 --> 00:36:27.220
race, where the incentive
system has actually

00:36:27.220 --> 00:36:30.800
built this massive race toward
massive amounts of computing

00:36:30.800 --> 00:36:31.300
power.

00:36:31.300 --> 00:36:33.740
And the concentration that's
been built around the mining

00:36:33.740 --> 00:36:37.160
pools on that basis leads
people to some concern

00:36:37.160 --> 00:36:40.524
that we could have a bad actor
one day taking 51% control.

00:36:40.524 --> 00:36:42.690
It hasn't happened until
now, and there are probably

00:36:42.690 --> 00:36:45.800
good game theory reasons as
to why that wouldn't happen.

00:36:45.800 --> 00:36:48.251
Who wants to destroy
their own value?

00:36:48.251 --> 00:36:50.000
But nonetheless, it's
a legitimate concern

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:52.500
that hangs over
Bitcoin all the time.

00:36:52.500 --> 00:36:54.325
And a lawyer from
a large company

00:36:54.325 --> 00:36:56.740
is probably going to feel
uncomfortable with that very

00:36:56.740 --> 00:36:58.195
risk always being there.

00:36:58.195 --> 00:37:00.320
And then there's this sort
of problem of consensus.

00:37:02.860 --> 00:37:06.140
Bitcoin's achievement
really was the capacity

00:37:06.140 --> 00:37:11.100
to incentivize-- to marry the
incentives of the individual

00:37:11.100 --> 00:37:12.850
to the interests of
the group, and to make

00:37:12.850 --> 00:37:14.890
sure these things
worked together.

00:37:14.890 --> 00:37:16.880
It resolved, in some
respects, the tragedy

00:37:16.880 --> 00:37:19.450
of the commons problem,
where we're all

00:37:19.450 --> 00:37:21.170
pursuing our self-interest
in destroying

00:37:21.170 --> 00:37:22.990
the public good that we have.

00:37:22.990 --> 00:37:28.880
But at the same time, the
model as it's structured

00:37:28.880 --> 00:37:31.720
limits the capacity to
sort of build out further.

00:37:31.720 --> 00:37:35.070
And so that same problem
starts to reemerge.

00:37:35.070 --> 00:37:37.160
In that, what really
would be probably better

00:37:37.160 --> 00:37:40.110
for Bitcoin is to
allow the capacity

00:37:40.110 --> 00:37:44.500
to innovate, to allow to
build this system out and grow

00:37:44.500 --> 00:37:48.854
on a-- in a more expansive
and innovative way.

00:37:48.854 --> 00:37:51.270
But if you have to keep getting
the consensus of everybody

00:37:51.270 --> 00:37:54.330
to do that, and nobody
wants to do so because it's

00:37:54.330 --> 00:37:56.080
against their own
personal interests,

00:37:56.080 --> 00:37:59.190
you once again are back to the
tragedy of the commons issue.

00:37:59.190 --> 00:38:00.640
It's kind of like the UN.

00:38:00.640 --> 00:38:03.125
It's impossible to get the
UN to do anything sometimes

00:38:03.125 --> 00:38:07.490
because you just need consensus,
and it's very hard to develop.

00:38:07.490 --> 00:38:13.370
But these problems
are being resolved.

00:38:13.370 --> 00:38:15.970
I mean, there really is
some remarkable amount

00:38:15.970 --> 00:38:19.680
of innovation going on, whether
it's Vitalik Buterin's project

00:38:19.680 --> 00:38:22.350
or it's what the guys at
Blockstream are doing,

00:38:22.350 --> 00:38:25.780
to try to build a side chain
that would allow innovation

00:38:25.780 --> 00:38:30.040
to happen in isolation
but connected to Bitcoin.

00:38:30.040 --> 00:38:32.010
There's a lot of work
going on in this space.

00:38:32.010 --> 00:38:35.420
But at the same time,
the corporate sector

00:38:35.420 --> 00:38:36.934
really doesn't care.

00:38:36.934 --> 00:38:39.350
They just want something that's
practical and commercially

00:38:39.350 --> 00:38:40.891
viable for them.

00:38:40.891 --> 00:38:43.140
And so they're focusing on
what they say they do like.

00:38:43.140 --> 00:38:44.440
They want to do
away with this coin

00:38:44.440 --> 00:38:46.540
that they think is just
too much of a distraction.

00:38:46.540 --> 00:38:48.789
And really, who cares about
whether the Fed goes away,

00:38:48.789 --> 00:38:52.196
and why do we need a
community currency anyway?

00:38:52.196 --> 00:38:54.570
Why can't we just deal with
some of the other cool things

00:38:54.570 --> 00:38:56.540
that this blockchain can do?

00:38:56.540 --> 00:38:58.190
And so they're
talking about some

00:38:58.190 --> 00:39:01.310
of these great ideas about
fully orderable databases,

00:39:01.310 --> 00:39:04.407
and how you could more
appropriately manage them.

00:39:04.407 --> 00:39:05.990
The idea of smart
contracts that might

00:39:05.990 --> 00:39:08.940
remove lawyers, and
escrow, and managers,

00:39:08.940 --> 00:39:11.520
and trustees from the
capacity of two entities

00:39:11.520 --> 00:39:13.170
to trade with each other.

00:39:13.170 --> 00:39:16.060
They like the idea of
peer-to-peer real-time payments

00:39:16.060 --> 00:39:19.280
and settlements to make
the ACH system-- well,

00:39:19.280 --> 00:39:23.960
to ultimately do away
with ACH and to improve

00:39:23.960 --> 00:39:26.270
the transfer of value
around the world

00:39:26.270 --> 00:39:29.530
and free up all this capital
that's tied up in that.

00:39:29.530 --> 00:39:31.460
Provable asset
registries, we talked--

00:39:31.460 --> 00:39:33.550
there's a brief reference
to it under [INAUDIBLE]

00:39:33.550 --> 00:39:38.390
in that earlier
presentation that Paul gave.

00:39:38.390 --> 00:39:40.380
And he's got this
idea that we could

00:39:40.380 --> 00:39:44.280
bring property title for
the poor of the world

00:39:44.280 --> 00:39:47.650
and place it onto a
blockchain, this idea

00:39:47.650 --> 00:39:52.790
that perhaps we could liberate
capital as a result of that.

00:39:52.790 --> 00:39:54.710
And then we could
turn securities

00:39:54.710 --> 00:39:57.750
into digitized products
and trade them.

00:39:57.750 --> 00:40:01.000
And so, there's a lot
of focus on these.

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:04.150
This is what they like
about blockchains.

00:40:04.150 --> 00:40:05.570
The advantages?

00:40:05.570 --> 00:40:09.464
None of this insane race
to-- concentrated mining

00:40:09.464 --> 00:40:11.130
and the arms race we
were talking about.

00:40:11.130 --> 00:40:13.550
It's a safe network,
because there's

00:40:13.550 --> 00:40:19.890
no threat of a 51% attack
when a central company would

00:40:19.890 --> 00:40:21.640
manage the blockchain itself.

00:40:21.640 --> 00:40:23.270
It would be scalable.

00:40:23.270 --> 00:40:25.890
If this was a
centralized model, you

00:40:25.890 --> 00:40:28.940
could just set it to the
parameters that you wanted.

00:40:28.940 --> 00:40:29.650
Fast.

00:40:29.650 --> 00:40:31.660
And this UN problem goes away.

00:40:31.660 --> 00:40:35.830
You don't need the consensus
of all of the participants

00:40:35.830 --> 00:40:38.400
to get things done.

00:40:38.400 --> 00:40:44.560
But ultimately, there's not much
in the way of disadvantages.

00:40:44.560 --> 00:40:46.130
But they're critical.

00:40:46.130 --> 00:40:50.840
The very fact of
centralization, and the return

00:40:50.840 --> 00:40:55.530
to the idea of trust, are
potentially dangerous.

00:40:55.530 --> 00:41:00.500
Now, it doesn't mean that
there isn't potentially

00:41:00.500 --> 00:41:02.490
an enormous amount of
value to be unleashed

00:41:02.490 --> 00:41:06.110
by moving to a centralized
blockchain that would do away

00:41:06.110 --> 00:41:09.090
with the problem of
the coins, particularly

00:41:09.090 --> 00:41:11.710
in a corporate setting.

00:41:11.710 --> 00:41:15.590
There's a bit of a debate about
why on earth you would do this.

00:41:15.590 --> 00:41:20.790
What benefit could you bring
to a company, when in fact you

00:41:20.790 --> 00:41:23.560
could just run a smart
database instead?

00:41:23.560 --> 00:41:25.475
Why do you need to build
this elaborate chain

00:41:25.475 --> 00:41:30.540
of interacting nodes
within your company

00:41:30.540 --> 00:41:33.480
to fulfill these functions?

00:41:33.480 --> 00:41:37.310
And there's actually been some
interesting work done on this.

00:41:37.310 --> 00:41:39.900
Tim Swanson, who is
in the audience here

00:41:39.900 --> 00:41:42.740
today has put out a really
interesting paper recently.

00:41:42.740 --> 00:41:46.340
People are focused on the idea
that there's a smart contract.

00:41:46.340 --> 00:41:48.020
That's really what Bitcoin is.

00:41:48.020 --> 00:41:50.120
And so you could
imagine-- and I think

00:41:50.120 --> 00:41:52.140
the jury is very much
still out whether this

00:41:52.140 --> 00:41:54.380
is going to function
this way or not--

00:41:54.380 --> 00:41:57.380
but a company could
perhaps set up

00:41:57.380 --> 00:42:02.020
a structure in which
different siloed units,

00:42:02.020 --> 00:42:05.680
different divisions within the
company that have for so long

00:42:05.680 --> 00:42:11.010
had to depend upon these rules
and processes, the requirement

00:42:11.010 --> 00:42:14.380
that XYZ manager has to sign
off on this RFQ and this guy

00:42:14.380 --> 00:42:16.240
has to do that.

00:42:16.240 --> 00:42:20.350
Anybody who has worked at a big
company, and all of you have,

00:42:20.350 --> 00:42:22.689
had kind of a management
and procurement or any level

00:42:22.689 --> 00:42:24.230
that deals with the
movement of funds

00:42:24.230 --> 00:42:26.870
and-- it can be incredibly
laborious, cumbersome,

00:42:26.870 --> 00:42:27.650
and bureaucratic.

00:42:27.650 --> 00:42:30.980
And the idea that you
could now use a blockchain

00:42:30.980 --> 00:42:34.820
to automate a lot of
those approval processes

00:42:34.820 --> 00:42:39.830
and maybe find interoperability
between differently

00:42:39.830 --> 00:42:45.420
arranged software stacks, and
different parts of the world,

00:42:45.420 --> 00:42:48.920
you could perhaps develop
efficiencies around that.

00:42:48.920 --> 00:42:51.480
Would it outweigh the cost of
building that system rather

00:42:51.480 --> 00:42:56.139
than, again, a more
sophisticated central database?

00:42:56.139 --> 00:42:56.680
I don't know.

00:42:56.680 --> 00:42:58.140
But I think the
point to make here

00:42:58.140 --> 00:43:00.290
is that, from a company
perspective, who cares?

00:43:00.290 --> 00:43:02.000
Like if you can
actually prove that,

00:43:02.000 --> 00:43:05.170
and a company can make life
more effective for them

00:43:05.170 --> 00:43:07.030
and save money, go for it.

00:43:07.030 --> 00:43:11.010
That's a way to bring value, and
every company should and would

00:43:11.010 --> 00:43:15.340
pursue anything that's going to
save money internally for them.

00:43:15.340 --> 00:43:17.900
The concern, to get back
to this problem about why

00:43:17.900 --> 00:43:20.030
centralization and
trust matter, is

00:43:20.030 --> 00:43:22.530
not for that kind of a
centralized blockchain,

00:43:22.530 --> 00:43:24.320
but what's being
sort of described

00:43:24.320 --> 00:43:28.630
as the federated
Blockchain-- the idea

00:43:28.630 --> 00:43:33.520
that an association of
entities with a shared

00:43:33.520 --> 00:43:38.840
interest in something
ends up working together

00:43:38.840 --> 00:43:42.590
to supplant the role that
the miners currently play.

00:43:42.590 --> 00:43:44.880
In a permissionless
environment, you'd

00:43:44.880 --> 00:43:46.400
have permissioned members.

00:43:46.400 --> 00:43:51.330
Now, the example I have
there is the TBTF alliance.

00:43:51.330 --> 00:43:53.990
Too Big To Fail, of course,
is the reference there.

00:43:53.990 --> 00:43:56.150
And I wanted to
throw out the idea

00:43:56.150 --> 00:44:02.110
that, as those banks that are
getting interested in Bitcoin

00:44:02.110 --> 00:44:04.619
and Blockchain right
now explore what

00:44:04.619 --> 00:44:06.160
seems to be one of
the things they're

00:44:06.160 --> 00:44:10.920
most interested in, which
is a more efficient process

00:44:10.920 --> 00:44:14.060
through which money and
securities are settled

00:44:14.060 --> 00:44:17.850
around the world, removing
middleman-- making

00:44:17.850 --> 00:44:21.510
that process far quicker than it
currently is, so that you move

00:44:21.510 --> 00:44:23.030
from three days,
to one week, down

00:44:23.030 --> 00:44:28.810
to virtually real-time, freeing
up massive amounts of capital

00:44:28.810 --> 00:44:29.500
in the process.

00:44:29.500 --> 00:44:32.479
Trillions of dollars a
day are traded in world

00:44:32.479 --> 00:44:33.520
foreign exchange markets.

00:44:33.520 --> 00:44:36.370
If we could get that money
to flow instantaneously,

00:44:36.370 --> 00:44:38.820
the impact on the globe
could be profound.

00:44:38.820 --> 00:44:41.050
There could be great savings
for the global economy.

00:44:41.050 --> 00:44:44.110
The problem is
that, if that were

00:44:44.110 --> 00:44:51.300
done in a model that is
controlled by the SIFIs,

00:44:51.300 --> 00:44:54.650
the Systematically Important
Financial Institutions,

00:44:54.650 --> 00:44:56.470
as the bureaucrats
are now trying

00:44:56.470 --> 00:45:02.950
to deal with the mess that was
the 2008 crisis describe them,

00:45:02.950 --> 00:45:04.040
what are we doing?

00:45:04.040 --> 00:45:04.540
You know?

00:45:04.540 --> 00:45:09.210
We're once again
centralizing information

00:45:09.210 --> 00:45:11.940
around the power of
these institutions.

00:45:11.940 --> 00:45:16.740
And what 2008 told
us was that it's not

00:45:16.740 --> 00:45:22.260
just that centralization
inherently breeds monopolies

00:45:22.260 --> 00:45:24.990
and therefore
rent-seeking activities,

00:45:24.990 --> 00:45:29.250
and ultimately denies
people the chance

00:45:29.250 --> 00:45:32.630
to obtain products
at a fair price.

00:45:32.630 --> 00:45:35.850
But it also, when
pushed to the extreme,

00:45:35.850 --> 00:45:38.300
and certainly when backed
by the political support

00:45:38.300 --> 00:45:43.400
that the implicit backstop
that we taxpayers gave to banks

00:45:43.400 --> 00:45:47.630
does, it can be really
destructive to society.

00:45:47.630 --> 00:45:50.180
We centralize
information and control

00:45:50.180 --> 00:45:55.050
around institutions that
have controlled the system,

00:45:55.050 --> 00:45:58.340
and it can do an enormous
amount of damage.

00:45:58.340 --> 00:45:59.880
And here's the point.

00:45:59.880 --> 00:46:05.580
Whereby if I think about Google
as a centralized institution,

00:46:05.580 --> 00:46:10.000
and its own clear
profit-seeking motives

00:46:10.000 --> 00:46:13.060
is different from a bank, is
because the infrastructure

00:46:13.060 --> 00:46:19.220
in which a bank is
operating-- the banks own it.

00:46:19.220 --> 00:46:24.380
It is already a centralized,
controlled platform.

00:46:24.380 --> 00:46:25.520
Right?

00:46:25.520 --> 00:46:29.990
TCP/IP, for whatever it's
worth, is an open system.

00:46:29.990 --> 00:46:30.580
It is there.

00:46:30.580 --> 00:46:32.730
And that is the thing
that makes Google continue

00:46:32.730 --> 00:46:34.450
to be an innovative company.

00:46:34.450 --> 00:46:36.730
And regardless of
whatever the EU ends up

00:46:36.730 --> 00:46:40.490
saying about you guys, there is
a profound amount of innovation

00:46:40.490 --> 00:46:42.960
that happens here,
precisely because you never

00:46:42.960 --> 00:46:46.095
know when the next competitor,
disruptive competitor,

00:46:46.095 --> 00:46:48.600
is going to be coming
over the horizon.

00:46:48.600 --> 00:46:51.980
And that is possible
because the infrastructure

00:46:51.980 --> 00:46:55.410
is available to all
to exploit, to create

00:46:55.410 --> 00:46:58.700
disruptive,
innovative new ideas.

00:46:58.700 --> 00:47:01.300
As we move into the age
of the internet of money,

00:47:01.300 --> 00:47:05.690
where we're trying to move
value into this same powerful,

00:47:05.690 --> 00:47:09.340
seamless, programmable world
that the rest of the world

00:47:09.340 --> 00:47:11.110
has already moved into.

00:47:11.110 --> 00:47:16.080
The real risk here is that
we deny that same capacity

00:47:16.080 --> 00:47:18.720
to the banking system,
and that we end up

00:47:18.720 --> 00:47:23.450
with a recentralized
model around

00:47:23.450 --> 00:47:24.549
the actual infrastructure.

00:47:24.549 --> 00:47:26.340
We don't care about
what the app makers can

00:47:26.340 --> 00:47:29.640
do-- what the banks and
their profit seeking entities

00:47:29.640 --> 00:47:30.430
can do there.

00:47:34.700 --> 00:47:36.600
What matters is
the infrastructure.

00:47:36.600 --> 00:47:38.640
What matters is the platform.

00:47:38.640 --> 00:47:44.900
So the concern is that, as we go
around this debate, blockchain

00:47:44.900 --> 00:47:46.340
without Bitcoin,
the idea that we

00:47:46.340 --> 00:47:49.020
can have some sort of
coinless structure here,

00:47:49.020 --> 00:47:53.879
I think it's absolutely
critical that we--

00:47:53.879 --> 00:47:55.420
those of us who are
invested in this,

00:47:55.420 --> 00:47:57.110
but I mean that as a society.

00:47:57.110 --> 00:47:59.650
Because this truly
is an idea that

00:47:59.650 --> 00:48:05.080
is far bigger than the
kind of hobbyist notion

00:48:05.080 --> 00:48:07.460
that people in the general
mainstream still think

00:48:07.460 --> 00:48:08.750
Bitcoin is.

00:48:08.750 --> 00:48:12.400
There are really profoundly
important issues at stake.

00:48:12.400 --> 00:48:14.000
So those of us that
are invested in

00:48:14.000 --> 00:48:20.420
that-- be they writers, techies,
or people in the finance world,

00:48:20.420 --> 00:48:24.510
it's beholden upon
us to try to fight

00:48:24.510 --> 00:48:28.970
for the guarantee of some sort
of decentralized, open sourced

00:48:28.970 --> 00:48:31.660
basis to this transformation.

00:48:31.660 --> 00:48:35.520
And companies could,
and should, and will

00:48:35.520 --> 00:48:36.780
do what they need to do.

00:48:36.780 --> 00:48:42.080
And blockchains that are able
to operate in efficient ways

00:48:42.080 --> 00:48:46.820
internally may well
be a fabulous solution

00:48:46.820 --> 00:48:48.900
for that process.

00:48:48.900 --> 00:48:50.960
But I just think that
the passion actually

00:48:50.960 --> 00:48:55.240
