00:49:56.807 --> 00:49:59.390
MALE SPEAKER: We're going to use
the microphone for questions,

00:49:59.390 --> 00:50:00.230
please.

00:50:00.230 --> 00:50:01.480
AUDIENCE: Thanks for the talk.

00:50:01.480 --> 00:50:02.611
It was pretty good.

00:50:02.611 --> 00:50:04.860
What are your thoughts on
the centralization of mining

00:50:04.860 --> 00:50:06.130
that's currently going on?

00:50:06.130 --> 00:50:07.380
I know a lot of the
fringe dwellers,

00:50:07.380 --> 00:50:08.990
including me, were
able to participate

00:50:08.990 --> 00:50:11.010
in that part of the
decentralized system.

00:50:11.010 --> 00:50:14.870
But since about a year,
I think that's pretty

00:50:14.870 --> 00:50:15.930
much over for everybody.

00:50:15.930 --> 00:50:19.410
So it's just a large-- couple
of large data center companies

00:50:19.410 --> 00:50:23.250
that own most of
the mining hardware.

00:50:23.250 --> 00:50:25.430
How do you think that
that will affect Bitcoin

00:50:25.430 --> 00:50:27.110
as a decentralized platform?

00:50:27.110 --> 00:50:29.318
MICHAEL CASEY: I think it's
the most important issue.

00:50:29.318 --> 00:50:32.435
I mean, it's-- and again, this
is part of-- the debate gets

00:50:32.435 --> 00:50:34.060
focused on, oh,
Bitcoin's too volatile.

00:50:34.060 --> 00:50:35.430
And it's criminals.

00:50:35.430 --> 00:50:36.330
That's the issue.

00:50:36.330 --> 00:50:39.770
Because that talks to the
core problem of the consensus

00:50:39.770 --> 00:50:42.200
infrastructure and
how it builds out.

00:50:42.200 --> 00:50:44.630
Now, is it a problem
that we have this?

00:50:44.630 --> 00:50:46.544
It's certainly a problem
for a little guy who

00:50:46.544 --> 00:50:47.835
wants to make some money in it.

00:50:50.340 --> 00:50:55.840
To me, the issue is
around whether or not

00:50:55.840 --> 00:50:57.710
there is a 51% attack concern.

00:50:57.710 --> 00:51:00.050
Really, that's ultimately it.

00:51:00.050 --> 00:51:03.960
I'd love to think that we would
be in a more democratic world,

00:51:03.960 --> 00:51:06.210
and everybody could
participate in it.

00:51:06.210 --> 00:51:09.540
And that is also an ideal that
I think is worth pursuing.

00:51:09.540 --> 00:51:14.500
But I think a greater
concern is that it

00:51:14.500 --> 00:51:20.330
is exposed to insecurity if
it's just a case of just owning

00:51:20.330 --> 00:51:21.232
all the hardware.

00:51:21.232 --> 00:51:23.440
So I think the pools need
to be resolved as an issue,

00:51:23.440 --> 00:51:25.140
seriously.

00:51:25.140 --> 00:51:28.080
Now there may be ways to
do peer-to-peer pooling

00:51:28.080 --> 00:51:31.140
or something that
moves that aside.

00:51:31.140 --> 00:51:33.440
But the other issue
is, have a sort

00:51:33.440 --> 00:51:35.130
of pragmatic view
about the importance

00:51:35.130 --> 00:51:37.340
of working with
regulators and making sure

00:51:37.340 --> 00:51:41.270
that government has a view as to
how Bitcoin is going to evolve.

00:51:41.270 --> 00:51:44.160
And to the extent to which
that mining activity is now

00:51:44.160 --> 00:51:49.265
concentrated in China,
for example, a lot of it

00:51:49.265 --> 00:51:51.940
is these data pools
that are based

00:51:51.940 --> 00:51:54.440
behind state-owned enterprises.

00:51:54.440 --> 00:51:57.270
Where the Beijing government
doesn't know they're there,

00:51:57.270 --> 00:52:01.770
but some party
[INAUDIBLE] is paid off,

00:52:01.770 --> 00:52:04.280
or is being paid off, rather,
by the Bitcoin miner who's

00:52:04.280 --> 00:52:06.830
using the free electricity
that's subsidized by the state

00:52:06.830 --> 00:52:08.070
to run this thing.

00:52:08.070 --> 00:52:11.660
That's hardly the kind of
comfortable infrastructure

00:52:11.660 --> 00:52:14.190
that the US government's
going to look to as

00:52:14.190 --> 00:52:17.970
the foundation for this system.

00:52:17.970 --> 00:52:21.830
So [INAUDIBLE] that's being done
by companies here in the US--

00:52:21.830 --> 00:52:23.680
Bitfury is one of
them-- to try to build

00:52:23.680 --> 00:52:25.680
a bridge to regulators,
to be much more

00:52:25.680 --> 00:52:30.690
transparent about their
activities, how much control

00:52:30.690 --> 00:52:34.290
they have over mining, where
their data centers are based

00:52:34.290 --> 00:52:35.700
and so forth.

00:52:35.700 --> 00:52:38.090
That's probably the most
important issue right now.

00:52:38.090 --> 00:52:40.750
I don't know how easily
we can wind back the clock

00:52:40.750 --> 00:52:44.710
and allow you to
participate at this stage.

00:52:44.710 --> 00:52:47.160
But certainly, making
sure that the threat

00:52:47.160 --> 00:52:50.380
of a 51% attack and that the
security is under control,

00:52:50.380 --> 00:52:53.910
that's just paramount
as far as I'm concerned.

00:52:53.910 --> 00:52:56.010
AUDIENCE: Michael,
could you do me a favor?

00:52:56.010 --> 00:52:59.340
For the audience on
YouTube who don't know what

00:52:59.340 --> 00:53:02.500
a 51% attack is, could
you go into details

00:53:02.500 --> 00:53:03.830
of what it actually means.

00:53:03.830 --> 00:53:04.360
MICHAEL CASEY: Absolutely.

00:53:04.360 --> 00:53:04.650
OK.

00:53:04.650 --> 00:53:05.150
Sure.

00:53:05.150 --> 00:53:05.990
Yes.

00:53:05.990 --> 00:53:06.940
I forget with the
YouTube audience

00:53:06.940 --> 00:53:08.814
we've got a different
audience from this one.

00:53:08.814 --> 00:53:14.900
So a 51% attack is the
notion that-- the blockchain

00:53:14.900 --> 00:53:18.950
is a verifiable record of all
of the transactions taking place

00:53:18.950 --> 00:53:23.880
in Bitcoin so long as we
can assume that nobody has

00:53:23.880 --> 00:53:29.240
the power to manipulate
transactions and actually

00:53:29.240 --> 00:53:33.820
have the system approve
fraudulent transactions,

00:53:33.820 --> 00:53:36.800
transactions that were double
spent, is the classic problem

00:53:36.800 --> 00:53:37.800
that people [INAUDIBLE].

00:53:37.800 --> 00:53:40.430
Kind of a form of digital
counterfeiting, if you like.

00:53:40.430 --> 00:53:43.640
And the reason why it would
be possible with a 51% attack

00:53:43.640 --> 00:53:47.830
is because, if you
owned more than 50%

00:53:47.830 --> 00:53:54.730
of all of the computing power
that is distributed to manage

00:53:54.730 --> 00:53:58.810
and confirm the transactions
in the blockchain, then

00:53:58.810 --> 00:54:02.370
by virtue of the way that
the algorithm creates

00:54:02.370 --> 00:54:10.930
the blockchain chain, you'd be
able to consistently enough win

00:54:10.930 --> 00:54:14.460
the awards for preparing
a block and would

00:54:14.460 --> 00:54:17.080
be able to build blocks
of your own interest.

00:54:17.080 --> 00:54:19.420
And that block would
become the longest chain.

00:54:19.420 --> 00:54:23.450
Bitcoin is built around the
idea that the longer the chain

00:54:23.450 --> 00:54:25.010
of transactions,
the longer of blocks

00:54:25.010 --> 00:54:29.360
in the transactions, that is
the de facto legitimate block

00:54:29.360 --> 00:54:29.860
chain.

00:54:29.860 --> 00:54:32.270
And that is basically
the burden of proof,

00:54:32.270 --> 00:54:34.070
that all the data
behind it is true.

00:54:34.070 --> 00:54:35.750
So if you had 51%,
you'd actually

00:54:35.750 --> 00:54:37.880
be able to more consistently
build the next block.

00:54:37.880 --> 00:54:39.550
And you'd have
the longest chain.

00:54:39.550 --> 00:54:41.217
You could ultimately
destroy the system,

00:54:41.217 --> 00:54:42.633
because you could
put whatever you

00:54:42.633 --> 00:54:44.480
want into those
transactions, and the system

00:54:44.480 --> 00:54:46.810
would regard that as the truth.

00:54:46.810 --> 00:54:50.150
So that's the sort of
complicated problem

00:54:50.150 --> 00:54:52.160
that a 51% attack is.

00:54:52.160 --> 00:54:55.420
And it's something
that's really been

00:54:55.420 --> 00:55:00.620
of great concern and a lot
of debate for some time.

00:55:00.620 --> 00:55:03.210
AUDIENCE: I've got a question
for both Michael and for Paul.

00:55:03.210 --> 00:55:06.060
For Michael, real quick, if
you do trust the transparency,

00:55:06.060 --> 00:55:08.480
if you have to identify
