to be part of the network?

00:55:17.137 --> 00:55:18.720
MICHAEL CASEY: You
know, I don't know.

00:55:18.720 --> 00:55:21.822
If you assume that that's an
inherent part of the thing--

00:55:21.822 --> 00:55:22.530
now I don't know.

00:55:22.530 --> 00:55:26.551
Maybe there's different
degrees of documentation.

00:55:26.551 --> 00:55:27.800
Maybe there's certain aspects.

00:55:27.800 --> 00:55:29.680
You don't know
exactly where it is.

00:55:29.680 --> 00:55:32.720
To be honest, I don't
know technically

00:55:32.720 --> 00:55:36.070
enough to understand how
far you would push that.

00:55:36.070 --> 00:55:41.330
But certainly, the idea of
some transparency behind it--

00:55:42.090 --> 00:55:43.460
MALE SPEAKER: Wasn't the
whole network designed so you

00:55:43.460 --> 00:55:44.380
don't have to be transparent?

00:55:44.380 --> 00:55:46.150
Like it's the assumption
that every actor

00:55:46.150 --> 00:55:47.580
is supposed to be
pseud-anonymous

00:55:47.580 --> 00:55:51.585
and has its own incentives to
do a certain type of action?

00:55:51.585 --> 00:55:52.460
MICHAEL CASEY: Right.

00:55:52.460 --> 00:55:55.870
But maybe there's
some degree to which

00:55:55.870 --> 00:56:00.400
there's enough
information out there

00:56:00.400 --> 00:56:04.070
about who's involved, who's
acting, how much you control,

00:56:04.070 --> 00:56:07.390
that is at least going to
bring some sort of security

00:56:07.390 --> 00:56:08.210
that network.

00:56:08.210 --> 00:56:12.390
Even if where your nodes
are and who you are

00:56:12.390 --> 00:56:13.957
is not actually
sort of necessarily

00:56:13.957 --> 00:56:15.040
identified as who you are.

00:56:15.040 --> 00:56:16.860
I mean, I don't know
exactly if it is.

00:56:16.860 --> 00:56:20.770
But I think it's hard to
deny that, for the sake

00:56:20.770 --> 00:56:22.670
of confidence and
trust in the system,

00:56:22.670 --> 00:56:23.020
I think this is one of the
things that often comes--

00:56:23.020 --> 00:56:24.200
AUDIENCE: But isn't it
supposed to be trustless?

00:56:24.200 --> 00:56:24.840
I mean, why should
you have trust?

00:56:25.110 --> 00:56:26.943
MICHAEL CASEY: The
trustless and trust thing

00:56:26.943 --> 00:56:31.780
I find-- to me, trustlessness is
this sort of holy grail concept

00:56:31.780 --> 00:56:33.820
that bitcoiners have
obviously held up

00:56:33.820 --> 00:56:35.240
as an important principle.

00:56:35.240 --> 00:56:36.823
But at the same time,
it's never going

00:56:36.823 --> 00:56:40.030
to get anywhere unless there's
trust in the system itself

00:56:40.030 --> 00:56:43.570
from people who use it, and
therefore from the government.

00:56:43.570 --> 00:56:45.870
Trust and confidence is
the essence of money.

00:56:45.870 --> 00:56:49.220
So building some degree of
transparency, and openness,

00:56:49.220 --> 00:56:50.720
and accountability,
around those who

00:56:50.720 --> 00:56:54.470
are working in
this system I think

00:56:54.470 --> 00:56:58.240
is an important compromise,
a bridging thing

00:56:58.240 --> 00:57:00.450
between those two concepts.

00:57:00.450 --> 00:57:03.782
Where you overstep the line and
suddenly destroy all the value,

00:57:03.782 --> 00:57:05.990
because all of a sudden,
you've lost the pseudonymity

00:57:05.990 --> 00:57:07.820
and so forth, I don't know.

00:57:07.820 --> 00:57:12.614
But it is-- it's
important to recognize

00:57:12.614 --> 00:57:13.905
that there's a challenge in it.

00:57:13.905 --> 00:57:18.330
PAUL VIGNA: And I think to
real true believers in Bitcoin,

00:57:18.330 --> 00:57:19.970
this is a core issue, right?

00:57:19.970 --> 00:57:23.970
The whole issue of identity,
pseudonymity, anonymity.

00:57:23.970 --> 00:57:28.175
But to most people, I don't
think they really care.

00:57:28.175 --> 00:57:29.310
Most people don't care.

00:57:29.310 --> 00:57:31.630
Most people
broadcast their lives

00:57:31.630 --> 00:57:36.885
on social media and they--
I think this idea of privacy

00:57:36.885 --> 00:57:38.170
has been so eroded.

00:57:38.170 --> 00:57:40.700
I think most people just
really don't care about it.

00:57:40.700 --> 00:57:41.992
They want a product that works.

00:57:41.992 --> 00:57:43.324
I think it's an important issue.

00:57:43.324 --> 00:57:44.410
I'm not saying it's not.

00:57:44.410 --> 00:57:46.960
But I'm saying that I could
see somebody like BitFury

00:57:46.960 --> 00:57:51.190
or somebody else come along and
build a system that does not

00:57:51.190 --> 00:57:55.540
put anonymity as its Godhead
and still build a product

00:57:55.540 --> 00:57:57.160
that people would use.

00:57:57.160 --> 00:57:59.760
It's just a matter of what
you think philosophically.

00:57:59.760 --> 00:58:01.410
AUDIENCE: I have one
question for you then, Paul,

00:58:01.410 --> 00:58:03.550
since I already picked
on Michael a little bit.

00:58:03.550 --> 00:58:06.900
So you mentioned Bitcoin's
in its early stages.

00:58:06.900 --> 00:58:10.560
Maybe it's early stages for
investors who just picked up

00:58:10.560 --> 00:58:13.477
on it, or journalists, or people
interested on the outside.

00:58:13.477 --> 00:58:15.310
But from like a network
