00:59:06.100 --> 00:59:07.510
could do it on your own again.

00:59:07.510 --> 00:59:09.600
And the entire
system resets itself,

00:59:09.600 --> 00:59:12.420
and you have a very
different makeup

00:59:12.420 --> 00:59:14.490
of people comprising
the system than what

00:59:14.490 --> 00:59:16.040
you're talking about now.

00:59:16.040 --> 00:59:17.180
That could happen.

00:59:17.180 --> 00:59:20.030
And personally, I
think Bitcoin's price,

00:59:20.030 --> 00:59:22.706
if it does survive
as a product, if it

00:59:22.706 --> 00:59:24.580
does survive as a
protocol, I think the price

00:59:24.580 --> 00:59:26.150
is going to come down.

00:59:26.150 --> 00:59:28.990
Because I think as
its utility gets

00:59:28.990 --> 00:59:31.585
proven out, its usefulness
on a day to day basis,

00:59:31.585 --> 00:59:34.460
it becomes less-- it
becomes demystified.

00:59:34.460 --> 00:59:35.850
It becomes less speculative.

00:59:35.850 --> 00:59:39.270
It becomes just this thing
that exists that you use.

00:59:39.270 --> 00:59:42.487
Nobody's going to want to pay
$200 for it or $1,000 for it.

00:59:42.487 --> 00:59:43.820
They might think it's worth $30.

00:59:43.820 --> 00:59:45.800
They might think it's worth $1.

00:59:45.800 --> 00:59:49.400
It becomes much more useful,
and much less valuable.

00:59:49.400 --> 00:59:51.860
Kind of like you wouldn't
pay $1,000 for a hammer,

00:59:51.860 --> 00:59:56.590
but you'd pay $12.50 for
a good hammer from Sears.

00:59:56.590 --> 00:59:58.140
And that's
idealistically speaking.

00:59:58.140 --> 01:00:01.190
That would be a big problem
for the people who have bought

01:00:01.190 --> 01:00:02.810
into the system right now.

01:00:02.810 --> 01:00:04.357
But I could see that happening.

01:00:04.357 --> 01:00:06.190
And you have a shakeout,
and it's a problem.

01:00:06.190 --> 01:00:08.790
But other people will
come in, and the system

01:00:08.790 --> 01:00:11.160
will reset itself and move on.

01:00:11.160 --> 01:00:15.804
So you know, it could go
through some senior moments,

01:00:15.804 --> 01:00:16.720
you might want to say.

01:00:16.720 --> 01:00:18.590
But I don't think
that necessarily

01:00:18.590 --> 01:00:21.471
has to be a death nail for it.

01:00:21.471 --> 01:00:23.470
MICHAEL CASEY: On the
question of fees replacing

01:00:23.470 --> 01:00:25.400
Bitcoin rewards, and
this notion that we've

01:00:25.400 --> 01:00:29.860
gone to a point where that's
just no longer viable, yes,

01:00:29.860 --> 01:00:31.210
it's obviously a challenge.

01:00:31.210 --> 01:00:33.510
And I suppose the question
becomes, like anywhere else,

01:00:33.510 --> 01:00:34.890
where's the value proposition?

01:00:34.890 --> 01:00:40.240
I mean, if ultimately the
fees have to rise to a level

01:00:40.240 --> 01:00:45.590
that they exceed-- we end up
with transaction processing

01:00:45.590 --> 01:00:47.740
fees that are something
like credit card and Visa,

01:00:47.740 --> 01:00:49.120
than what's the point, right?

01:00:49.120 --> 01:00:53.800
So there's a concern, and
it's a legitimate one.

01:00:53.800 --> 01:00:56.100
And I know there's a
big debate about, well,

01:00:56.100 --> 01:00:58.490
if we start putting all
this extra value on top

01:00:58.490 --> 01:01:00.990
of the blockchain and
trading large property

01:01:00.990 --> 01:01:02.660
securities and so
forth, who would

01:01:02.660 --> 01:01:05.247
want to do that if there's not
enough background security?

01:01:05.247 --> 01:01:07.080
To Paul's point, they
actually probably want

01:01:07.080 --> 01:01:08.895
the value to rise higher
so that you have--

01:01:08.895 --> 01:01:10.520
to the opposite of
that, so that you've

01:01:10.520 --> 01:01:15.570
got enough of a security basis
for big transactions to happen.

01:01:15.570 --> 01:01:19.020
The question that becomes how
economical does that become,

01:01:19.020 --> 01:01:22.510
and what miners-- it's kind
of like to me, you know,

01:01:22.510 --> 01:01:23.200
we don't know.

01:01:23.200 --> 01:01:23.350
Right?

01:01:23.350 --> 01:01:25.308
I mean, there's just this
huge, big experiment.

01:01:25.308 --> 01:01:27.456
What is going to be
demanded, and what's

01:01:27.456 --> 01:01:29.080
going to become--
what are miners going

01:01:29.080 --> 01:01:35.080
to need in return for processing
the amount of information

01:01:35.080 --> 01:01:37.540
that's going to passing
across this blockchain?

01:01:37.540 --> 01:01:40.740
And I just-- it's
an article of faith,

01:01:40.740 --> 01:01:44.780
but I think there is a sense
that these problems can

01:01:44.780 --> 01:01:45.480
be resolved.

01:01:45.480 --> 01:01:46.980
I mean, we've gotten this far.

01:01:46.980 --> 01:01:48.100
I don't know how.

01:01:48.100 --> 01:01:51.870
You can have a much
better grip on how

01:01:51.870 --> 01:01:54.590
this thing would actually
be physically designed.

01:01:54.590 --> 01:01:58.347
But I just feel as if we've
proved-- it's lasted this long.

01:01:58.347 --> 01:01:59.930
It actually has--
to your point, maybe

01:01:59.930 --> 01:02:01.889
it has become the senior
citizen in that sense.

01:02:01.889 --> 01:02:03.805
The good side of that,
it's actually survived.

01:02:03.805 --> 01:02:04.910
It hasn't been destroyed.

01:02:04.910 --> 01:02:07.010
It has actually
functioned to this point.

01:02:07.010 --> 01:02:09.820
And there's a lot of innovation
and money and interest

01:02:09.820 --> 01:02:11.410
in making this thing work.

01:02:11.410 --> 01:02:14.200
And on that basis,
I feel as if there's

01:02:14.200 --> 01:02:15.490
going to be ways to innovate.

01:02:15.490 --> 01:02:16.960
It might not be the economy.

01:02:16.960 --> 01:02:20.030
It really is going to
be a problem, perhaps.

01:02:20.030 --> 01:02:22.374
The 21 million
might be the limit.

01:02:22.374 --> 01:02:24.620
The compensation
system just might not

01:02:24.620 --> 01:02:28.210
be sufficient to sustain this.

01:02:28.210 --> 01:02:31.590
But at the same time, we've
got the workings of a model.

01:02:31.590 --> 01:02:34.501
We have the
blockchain as an idea.

01:02:34.501 --> 01:02:36.000
And my point is
simply that whatever

01:02:36.000 --> 01:02:38.690
shape it takes, whether it's
a Ethereum or something else,

01:02:38.690 --> 01:02:41.220
decentralization still
needs to be an objective.

01:02:41.220 --> 01:02:43.220
It needs to be a very
important objective of how

01:02:43.220 --> 01:02:44.961
we take this thing forward.

01:02:44.961 --> 01:02:46.710
AUDIENCE: But my
understanding of the pool

01:02:46.710 --> 01:02:49.600
is still a bunch of
different people, right?

01:02:49.600 --> 01:02:54.700
Who all-- they essentially don't
want to gamble with the, oh,

01:02:54.700 --> 01:02:56.860
might I find a
bitcoin ever or not.

01:02:56.860 --> 01:02:57.360
Right?

01:02:57.360 --> 01:03:00.140
They just want
some small portion

01:03:00.140 --> 01:03:07.980
of each bitcoin that's found,
proportional to how much

01:03:07.980 --> 01:03:08.500
they invest.

01:03:08.500 --> 01:03:09.370
Right?

01:03:09.370 --> 01:03:12.885
So how is this a danger?

01:03:12.885 --> 01:03:14.635
MICHAEL CASEY: Well,
it's a danger because

01:03:14.635 --> 01:03:15.660
of the way that the server--

01:03:15.660 --> 01:03:17.110
PAUL VIGNA: We're talking about
two different things, right?

01:03:17.110 --> 01:03:18.902
I mean, you're talking
about the big pools.

01:03:18.902 --> 01:03:20.776
You're talking about
basically the contracts,

01:03:20.776 --> 01:03:21.740
the hashing contracts.

01:03:21.740 --> 01:03:22.240
Right?

01:03:22.240 --> 01:03:24.160
You're like, you buy a
contract, and somebody

01:03:24.160 --> 01:03:27.007
has a small [INAUDIBLE], and
you get a little piece of it.

01:03:27.007 --> 01:03:27.840
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

01:03:27.840 --> 01:03:29.480
AUDIENCE: No, I'm
talking about mining.

01:03:29.480 --> 01:03:30.260
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

01:03:30.260 --> 01:03:30.860
MICHAEL CASEY:
--contract, or you

01:03:30.860 --> 01:03:31.600
could be your own
separate miner.

01:03:31.600 --> 01:03:33.516
Either way, you still
belong to a pool, right?

01:03:33.516 --> 01:03:36.624
So the pool is the way
to efficiently distribute

01:03:36.624 --> 01:03:38.540
a piece of what's happening
rather than having

01:03:38.540 --> 01:03:40.290
to rely on the idea
that just once you

01:03:40.290 --> 01:03:42.710
might win the next
block three years hence.

01:03:42.710 --> 01:03:43.210
Right?

01:03:43.210 --> 01:03:45.060
So it's a way to
actually portion it out

01:03:45.060 --> 01:03:47.400
on a more steady
flow what that is.

01:03:47.400 --> 01:03:49.930
And that would be-- it
wouldn't be a problem at all

01:03:49.930 --> 01:03:51.900
if the pool
structure had nothing

01:03:51.900 --> 01:03:56.930
to do with voting power and
the application of the capacity

01:03:56.930 --> 01:04:04.550
to determine what the
shape of the blockchain is.

01:04:04.550 --> 01:04:05.660
But it's not like that.

01:04:05.660 --> 01:04:13.190
It is that the pool
itself, it has the capacity

01:04:13.190 --> 01:04:16.600
to actually set the next block.

01:04:16.600 --> 01:04:22.370
The pool becomes the
administrator of the block.

01:04:22.370 --> 01:04:26.710
It's drawing upon the hashing
power of all of its members

01:04:26.710 --> 01:04:29.100
to then becomes the next block.

01:04:29.100 --> 01:04:29.790
All right?

01:04:29.790 --> 01:04:32.479
So that gives it enormous
administrative power.

01:04:32.479 --> 01:04:34.270
I mean, that's why it
comes up all the time

01:04:34.270 --> 01:04:40.610
when GHash.IO, which was
one of the biggest pools,

01:04:40.610 --> 01:04:41.850
got over 51%.

01:04:41.850 --> 01:04:44.480
There was a some great concern
that they would use that power

01:04:44.480 --> 01:04:45.760
to launch the attack.

01:04:45.760 --> 01:04:47.560
Now, they didn't, because not
in their interest to do so.

01:04:47.560 --> 01:04:49.143
That's the other
point of this, right?

01:04:49.143 --> 01:04:50.760
Is why would you do it?

01:04:50.760 --> 01:04:54.540
That's proven to be enough
of a defense right now.

01:04:54.540 --> 01:04:56.450
But the very prospect
of it is still there.

01:04:56.450 --> 01:04:57.510
AUDIENCE: If they
did that, though, I

01:04:57.510 --> 01:04:58.790
mean it would be obvious.

01:04:58.790 --> 01:05:00.520
People would see it
happening, right?

01:05:00.520 --> 01:05:03.460
So would--

01:05:03.460 --> 01:05:06.610
PAUL VIGNA: I think, too, the
whole thing is-- you know,

01:05:06.610 --> 01:05:10.426
it's something that Nakamoto
addressed in the white paper.

01:05:10.426 --> 01:05:13.050
I mean, this was something-- he
was the first one to bring this

01:05:13.050 --> 01:05:15.800
up, this idea of a 51% attack.

01:05:15.800 --> 01:05:17.190
And he ultimately rejected it.

01:05:17.190 --> 01:05:19.510
Because it is ultimately
self-defeating, you're right.

01:05:19.510 --> 01:05:20.410
People would see it.

01:05:20.410 --> 01:05:21.820
They would understand it.

01:05:21.820 --> 01:05:26.260
And to the extent that somebody
did take over the blockchain,

01:05:26.260 --> 01:05:29.150
they would drive everybody else
out that then becomes useless,

01:05:29.150 --> 01:05:30.430
becomes valueless.

01:05:30.430 --> 01:05:32.630
And everything that they
invested, building up

01:05:32.630 --> 01:05:35.380
to 51% or more, becomes
completely-- they

01:05:35.380 --> 01:05:38.520
lose all their money on it.

01:05:38.520 --> 01:05:42.650
It's an issue, but I don't--
firstly, I agree with Nakamoto.

01:05:42.650 --> 01:05:45.807
I don't think it's going
to be a death knell

01:05:45.807 --> 01:05:46.640
problem for Bitcoin.

01:05:46.640 --> 01:05:48.306
When I don't think
it's going to happen,

01:05:48.306 --> 01:05:50.180
because ultimately
it is self-defeating.

01:05:50.180 --> 01:05:51.030
AUDIENCE: That wasn't
actually what I meant.

01:05:51.030 --> 01:05:52.671
I meant the
individual miners who

01:05:52.671 --> 01:05:54.420
are contributing to
the pool would notice,

01:05:54.420 --> 01:05:55.461
and then they would stop.

01:05:55.461 --> 01:05:56.350
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

01:05:56.514 --> 01:05:58.430
MICHAEL CASEY: But it's
the same point, right?

01:05:58.430 --> 01:06:01.016
Ultimately that you would
stop doing something

01:06:01.016 --> 01:06:03.140
that would destroy your
value, would leave the pool

01:06:03.140 --> 01:06:04.870
and diminish its power, and
therefore would no longer be

01:06:04.870 --> 01:06:05.453
able to do so.

01:06:08.352 --> 01:06:10.310
I don't know the degree
to which you even know.

01:06:10.310 --> 01:06:12.540
I mean, that there's fraudulent
transactions that are building.

01:06:12.540 --> 01:06:14.880
There's double spins that don't
necessarily get picked up.

01:06:14.880 --> 01:06:17.200
I mean, I don't know enough
about the technicalities of it.

01:06:17.200 --> 01:06:19.366
It's quite-- I would imagine
it's actually possible,

01:06:19.366 --> 01:06:20.400
for quite some time.

01:06:20.400 --> 01:06:21.900
There's been quite
a bit of research

01:06:21.900 --> 01:06:24.020
into whether 51%
attacks are possible

01:06:24.020 --> 01:06:26.040
and how it might
manifest itself.

01:06:27.495 --> 01:06:28.870
But it might go
on for some time.

01:06:28.870 --> 01:06:30.000
And all you're doing
is you're eroding

01:06:30.000 --> 01:06:31.770
the value of the--
people, unaware of it,

01:06:31.770 --> 01:06:34.700
are actually off what they
think is a legitimate chain,

01:06:34.700 --> 01:06:37.050
and in the process, they're
just actually undermining

01:06:37.050 --> 01:06:39.050
the reality and the
effectiveness of the system.

01:06:39.050 --> 01:06:40.032
Now, I don't know.

01:06:40.032 --> 01:06:41.240
Maybe somebody gets swindled.

01:06:41.240 --> 01:06:42.160
They raise their hand.

01:06:42.160 --> 01:06:42.910
The word gets out.

01:06:42.910 --> 01:06:43.740
Who knows?

01:06:43.740 --> 01:06:45.470
It could very well come out.

01:06:45.470 --> 01:06:47.510
But that would be the
defense mechanism-- I

01:06:47.510 --> 01:06:48.760
think you're absolutely right.

01:06:48.760 --> 01:06:50.970
The idea that you would
expect pool members to leave,

01:06:50.970 --> 01:06:52.386
diminish the power,
and that would

01:06:52.386 --> 01:06:55.139
become the self-regulating
system within that.

01:06:55.139 --> 01:06:56.680
The great concern
for me though, just

01:06:56.680 --> 01:06:58.170
from this whole
practical perspective,

01:06:58.170 --> 01:07:00.380
is how does this become used
from a commercial perspective

01:07:00.380 --> 01:07:01.930
and whether companies
get involved.

01:07:01.930 --> 01:07:05.130
If I'm a lawyer at a
Fortune 500 company,

01:07:05.130 --> 01:07:06.990
and I wanted to maybe
think I should start

01:07:06.990 --> 01:07:08.960
using Bitcoin for my
international procurement

01:07:08.960 --> 01:07:11.790
or something else, and I'm a
lawyer, it's like, no, look.

01:07:11.790 --> 01:07:13.445
I don't care.

01:07:13.445 --> 01:07:15.070
Whether or not this
is possible or not,

01:07:15.070 --> 01:07:18.827
this is big enough of a risk
that our-- whatever settlement

01:07:18.827 --> 01:07:20.910
that we think we've done
could be reversed however

01:07:20.910 --> 01:07:22.782
many months from now.

01:07:22.782 --> 01:07:23.740
It's just not worth it.

01:07:23.740 --> 01:07:24.240
Right?

01:07:24.240 --> 01:07:26.470
So lawyers are
incredibly cautious.

01:07:26.470 --> 01:07:29.270
And the very presence
of a 51% attack I think

01:07:29.270 --> 01:07:31.132
is a challenge for
that very reason.

01:07:31.132 --> 01:07:33.090
AUDIENCE: So I think some
of the early adopters

01:07:33.090 --> 01:07:37.750
got into Bitcoin principally
because it's a better gold

01:07:37.750 --> 01:07:39.260
to store a value.

01:07:39.260 --> 01:07:42.700
I think one of the questions
as to Bitcoin's survivability

01:07:42.700 --> 01:07:45.770
is what is it going to take
to the rest of the population

01:07:45.770 --> 01:07:48.310
to sort of appreciate
that use case?

01:07:48.310 --> 01:07:51.376
Do you have any
thoughts on that?

01:07:51.376 --> 01:07:52.750
PAUL VIGNA: It's
a good question.

01:07:52.750 --> 01:07:58.030
I mean, because I
don't know that there's

01:07:58.030 --> 01:07:59.190
a good answer for it.

01:07:59.190 --> 01:08:00.523
That's why it's a good question.

01:08:00.523 --> 01:08:03.260
I mean, it's a problem,
this idea of Bitcoin

01:08:03.260 --> 01:08:06.235
becoming a mainstream
product, it's a problem.

01:08:08.770 --> 01:08:10.942
However, the solution,
I think, is just time.

01:08:10.942 --> 01:08:13.400
This is something that is going
to have to prove itself out

01:08:13.400 --> 01:08:16.319
over a period of
years before people

01:08:16.319 --> 01:08:19.350
become comfortable enough that
they don't think about it.

01:08:19.350 --> 01:08:20.569
You know, it's funny.

01:08:20.569 --> 01:08:23.110
I was thinking about this on
the plane when I was coming over

01:08:23.110 --> 01:08:23.750
here yesterday.

01:08:23.750 --> 01:08:25.333
Because I came over
on a plane, right?

01:08:25.333 --> 01:08:27.704
So I flew from New York in
about five or six hours--

01:08:27.704 --> 01:08:28.284
MICHAEL CASEY: [INAUDIBLE].

01:08:28.284 --> 01:08:28.590
PAUL VIGNA: No.

01:08:28.590 --> 01:08:29.370
But, I mean, think about it.

01:08:29.370 --> 01:08:30.250
I got on a plane.

01:08:30.250 --> 01:08:32.700
I got on a giant
hulking piece of metal

01:08:32.700 --> 01:08:35.720
that went up 30,000 feet in
the air and in five hours

01:08:35.720 --> 01:08:38.439
transported me 3,000 miles.

01:08:38.439 --> 01:08:42.290
If anything goes wrong on
that plane, I am a dead man.

01:08:42.290 --> 01:08:42.939
Dead.

01:08:42.939 --> 01:08:43.750
30,000 feet?

01:08:43.750 --> 01:08:44.300
Forget it.

01:08:44.300 --> 01:08:44.800
It's gone.

01:08:44.800 --> 01:08:46.600
I got on a plane without
even thinking about it.

01:08:46.600 --> 01:08:47.250
I was excited.

01:08:47.250 --> 01:08:47.750
I was happy.

01:08:47.750 --> 01:08:49.666
I thought, oh, great,
I'm going to fall asleep

01:08:49.666 --> 01:08:50.380
in San Francisco.

01:08:50.380 --> 01:08:51.819
That's a great thing.

01:08:51.819 --> 01:08:53.950
Because the technology
has proven itself out

01:08:53.950 --> 01:08:55.200
over the course of a century.

01:08:55.200 --> 01:08:57.260
People don't even think
about getting on planes.

01:08:57.260 --> 01:08:59.176
People don't even think
about getting in a car

01:08:59.176 --> 01:09:01.729
and driving on a highway
at 80 miles an hour.

01:09:01.729 --> 01:09:05.250
Because the technology
has proven itself out

01:09:05.250 --> 01:09:07.630
over a long, long
period of time.

01:09:07.630 --> 01:09:10.580
Bitcoin is going to have to
go through that same proving

01:09:10.580 --> 01:09:13.794
period before the
mainstream people use it

01:09:13.794 --> 01:09:15.960
without even thinking about
it or worrying about it.

01:09:15.960 --> 01:09:16.918
Oh, it's digital money.

01:09:16.918 --> 01:09:18.810
Bitcoin, I'll pick one, boom.

01:09:18.810 --> 01:09:21.350
It's going to take time
for it to prove itself out.

01:09:21.350 --> 01:09:22.790
And if it can't
prove itself out,

01:09:22.790 --> 01:09:24.270
well, then it's just
going to die away.

01:09:24.270 --> 01:09:26.603
And it'll be another idea
that was neat and interesting,

01:09:26.603 --> 01:09:28.809
and got some adherence,
and didn't make it.

01:09:28.809 --> 01:09:29.550
MICHAEL CASEY: I'll
just have one last word

01:09:29.550 --> 01:09:31.550
that I think might
round this thing out.

01:09:31.550 --> 01:09:33.950
And that is that I think
absolutely we've kind

01:09:33.950 --> 01:09:37.734
of reached our plateau, our
limit for how many mainstream

01:09:37.734 --> 01:09:39.400
folks are going to
go and say, hey, this

01:09:39.400 --> 01:09:40.640
would be a great tool
for me to go on and buy

01:09:40.640 --> 01:09:41.390
my groceries with.

01:09:41.390 --> 01:09:44.170
And for all the reasons we cite,
it's just not a very attractive

01:09:44.170 --> 01:09:45.250
currency to be used.

01:09:45.250 --> 01:09:47.204
The big question,
then, is moving it

01:09:47.204 --> 01:09:49.620
to the next phase is how it
becomes adopted by companies--

01:09:49.620 --> 01:09:52.204
how it's adopted by corporates,
institutions, organizations.

01:09:52.204 --> 01:09:53.620
That's going to
be the next phase.

01:09:53.620 --> 01:09:55.010
And we're probably going to
have to go through that phase

01:09:55.010 --> 01:09:57.691
before we bring all of the
general public on board.

01:09:57.691 --> 01:09:59.940
That's why this question
that we're talking about here

01:09:59.940 --> 01:10:01.170
is important, because
these guys have

01:10:01.170 --> 01:10:02.880
got a different set
of motives from what

01:10:02.880 --> 01:10:04.240
the early adopters had.

01:10:04.240 --> 01:10:06.360
And that's why the
debate is critical.

01:10:06.360 --> 01:10:09.430
But I don't think we're going
to-- the idea, the dream

01:10:09.430 --> 01:10:12.020
that we would just sort of
automatically move gradually

01:10:12.020 --> 01:10:14.780
through the population, and we'd
all sort of start picking up

01:10:14.780 --> 01:10:17.320
this thing and using
it to pay for our gas

01:10:17.320 --> 01:10:19.520
or whatever, it
was a pipe dream.

01:10:19.520 --> 01:10:24.140
And therefore, the next phase
is this corporate phase.

01:10:24.140 --> 01:10:27.090
And how it plays
out is critical.

01:10:27.090 --> 01:10:28.850
So just a way to round it out.

01:10:28.850 --> 01:10:31.020
MALE SPEAKER: And on
that note, please join me

01:10:31.020 --> 01:10:32.690
in thanking Michael and Paul.

01:10:32.690 --> 01:10:35.539
[APPLAUSE]

